Title:     Accessing DLL data structures from WordBasic.
             (usage of data link libraries with Microsoft Word for
             Windows 2.0's programming language) (PC Tech: Extending your
             apps; technical; column)
Author:    Chen, Vincent
Attached:  DLLACC.EXE  Demonstrates DLL library use via WordBasic.

Abstract:  Programmers of Microsoft Windows applications such as Word for
           Windows (WFW) can streamline the process by utilizing some of
           Windows' dynamic link libraries (DLL) in their routines. DLLs,
           which are collections of named subroutines and functions, are
           brought into Windows only when a service is needed by an
           application; they are offloaded when no longer needed. WFW 2.0
           contains a powerful programming language called WordBasic,
           which can be used to customize nearly every aspect of the
           program. When coupled with DLLs, Windows' basic services may
           be controlled directly from the application. The basic process
           for using WordBasic to customize aspects of WFW is presented,
           complete with examples of data structures, which are at the
           heart of most Windows functions.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Full Text:

It shouldn't surprise anyone to learn that shrink-wrapped applications
are more powerful than ever before--giving users and developers alike
tremendous opportunities to increase productivity through customization.
In this issue, we inaugurate a new column called Extending Your Apps that
reflects the sophistication of applications that contain powerful
application development environments in their own right. In this space,
we'll cover a wide variety of topics that will let you extend your own
apps--LBLDDE, OLE, REXX, WordBasic, VBA, OpenDoc--a veritable alphabet
soup of techniques to get the most from your applications. First, we'll
show you how to extend WordBasic's power programming language to use
Windows' Common Dialog dynamic link library (DLL) file.

Windows programming isn't just for C and PASCAL programmers anymore. If
you're a Word for Windows 2.0 user, you've already got a powerful
programming language called WordBasic built right into your word
processor. You can use WordBasic to customize virtually every aspect of
Word for Windows: building new commands, replacing built-in functions,
and interacting with users through custom dialog boxes. You can even use
it to tap directly into and control Windows' basic services by accessing
Windows DLLs.

A dynamic link library is just a collection of named functions and
subroutines that provides certain services to Windows applications. They
are called dynamic because they are brought into Windows only when an
application requests a service and unloaded when they are no longer
needed. Windows and Windows applications use DLLs extensively to share
functions and manage memory resources. In fact, most of Windows itself is
actually contained within three dynamic link library files: USER, KERNEL,
and Graphics Device Interface (GDI), which collectively form the Windows
application programming interface (API).

Accessing DLLs lets you perform a lot of useful operations that ordinary
WordBasic commands can't handle, such as determining whether another
application is running, finding the screen resolution, getting the DOS
environment string, or even deciding if Program Manager is your default
shell. Other examples of operations can be found in PSS.DOC, a sample
file that comes with Word for Windows. Conspicuous by their absence from
PSS.DOC, however, are WordBasic examples that use the functions in
Windows 3.1's Common Dialog DLL (COMMDLG.DLL). This dynamic link library
is responsible for helping Windows and Windows applications to present a
common, familiar user interface; it provides standard dialog boxes for
such fundamental interface operations as file selection, font selection,
color selection, search-and-replace, and printer control.

Unfortunately for WordBasic programmers, COMMDLG relies on data
structures, which are programming constructs used by advanced programming
languages to group related variables into a single block of memory. In
languages such as C, Pascal, and Microsoft Visual Basic, the declaration
of a data structure provides a full listing of the members (or variables)
located within a memory block and their data types. This declaration lets
you access each member simply by using its name, and the programming
environment uses the declaration listing to figure out where that member
is located in the memory block.

WordBasic and most other application macro languages don't know how to
work with data structures. But we don't have to let this limitation stop
us. All we need to do is find a way to allow WordBasic to access
individual members of a data structure, either to set it to a value or to
return its value to WordBasic. Our DLL ACCES.DLL helper DLL (which you
can download from PC MagNet, along with the sample macros from this
article) provides the solution to this problem; it is WordBasic's gateway
to the members of the data structure.

Combine this with a few WordBasic convenience routines that help
WordBasic reserve a memory block of the correct size, add a few
organizational concepts, and you'll be able to use almost any DLL
functions that require data structures. I'll illustrate the use of these
routines and concepts by means of a few sample macros that use the
COMMDLG interface to enhance Word for Windows' FileOpen and FileSaveAs
commands. But you can use similar techniques with any programming
environment that can use DLLs; a category that includes the macro
languages from Ami Pro, Microsoft Excel, and even personal information
managers such as PackRat!

WHY REPLACE FILEOPEN?

One of Word for Windows' most serious file-handling deficiencies is its
inability to start the FileOpen dialog box with a filespec pattern other
than the default patterns of *.DOC (for Word files), *.DOT (for Word
template files), *.RTF (for rich text format files), or *.TXT (for text
files). As a direct result of this, many people simply use the .DOC
extension, keeping track of the type of document using subdirectories or
the first eight characters of the filename. Life would be much simpler,
however, if you could use the file extension in order to categorize your
documents by type. Imagine if all your contracts were named *.CNT,
letters *.LET, invoices *.INV, and so on, and if you could include these
extensions in the pattern list box in your file-selection dialog boxes,
as shown in Figure 1.

Although you can build custom dialog boxes in WordBasic, the FileOpen
dialog box is a bit more complex to manage, because it needs to access
the file system to build up its lists of drives, directories, and
filenames. The default WinWord FileOpen dialog box does this by using
built-in file-selection dialog boxes, but you can use the prebuilt dialog
boxes supplied by COMMDLG.DLL. With this DLL file, all you have to do is
provide some details, such as what directory to use, what type of files
to display, and what the title bar should say.

The COMMDLG interface functions are designed to be flexible, providing a
wide range of options to satisfy the needs of a great variety of possible
Windows applications. Rather than using separate function arguments for
the different options, each COMMDLG function uses a single argument,
which represents a data structure that packages all the options and all
the function results into a single, functional unit. Provided that both
the calling program and the COMMDLG function are in agreement on the
definition of a data structure, you can access this unit in a consistent
manner.

Normally, the procedure for doing this is relatively straightforward.
Before calling the COMMDLG function, the calling program creates the data
structure and sets some or all the members of the data structure for use
as input to the function. And before returning, the COMMDLG function sets
some or all the member variables to return results to the caller.

Since WordBasic has no concept of data structures, it can't be used to
access these COMMDLG functions directly. But luckily, these and most
other DLL functions use only the addresses--or memory locations--of data
structures as function arguments. These addresses are represented as long
integers. (This is commonly known as pass by reference--when the address,
not the actual value, of a variable is given to the function.) A
WordBasic macro, therefore, can access these functions indirectly by
declaring a data structure as type Long then using the structure's
address to locate its members.

Once WordBasic locates the data member, it just needs a bit of help
interpreting the data that's there. That's where DLLACCES.DLL comes in.
DLLACCES is a custom collection of functions that translates data at
specified memory locations to and from data types that WordBasic
understands: integer, long, double, and string. In essence, you can tell
DLLACCES to do something like "get me the long integer value of the
second data member of this structure," or "set the fifth data member of
this structure to the byte value 16, but I'm passing you an integer
(since WordBasic does not have a Byte type)."

To use the DLLACCES.DLL functions, you need some understanding of how
data structures are stored in memory. Figure 2 shows a memory block
containing the data structure called MyStruct, whose C-language
definition is to the left in the figure. This data structure contains
five members: one long integer, two integers, one string, and one
double-precision number. The rectangular blocks represent the memory each
variable occupies. The first variable--a long integer--uses 4 bytes, the
next two--both integers--use 2 bytes each, var4--the string--uses 4
bytes, and the double-precision variable uses 8 bytes.

The total size of the structure is 20 bytes. Thus, in order to find the
location of any variable in the structure from the beginning of its
memory block, just add up the sizes, in bytes, of all the variables that
come before it. That's what the labels to the left of each block
represent: the offset of each variable from the beginning of the
structure. A programming environment that supports data structures can
automatically calculate the offset for each data member and convert the
bytes located there to the value of the correct data type. But WordBasic
can't do this, so you must calculate the memory offset of each data
member manually, and then use the DLLACCES functions to convert the data
into a form that WordBasic can handle.

THE DLLACCES.DLL FILE

Let's take a look at some examples of how to use the DLLACCES functions
with the sample data structure MyStruct, shown in Figure 2. The assigning
of values to bytes, long integers, floating-point numbers,
double-precision numbers, and string variables in WordBasic is
accomplished by means of a series of DA_Set functions. (The exact syntax
of which you'll find in DLLACCES.DOC, which documents the entire suite of
DLLACCES functions and gives detailed instructions for calculating these
address offsets.)

Say, for instance, that you have the memory location of a MyStruct data
structure stored in a variable called lpStruct, and you want to set its
third member (var3) to the value 48. Since this value is an integer
value, you'd use the DLLACCES function that sets integer variables
(DA_SetInt), providing the function with the memory location of the data
structure, the offset of the data member you're interested in (in this
case, 6 bytes), and the value you want to assign to the data member:

var3Offset = 6 result = DA_SetInt(lpStruct,
var3Offset, 48)

The result of the function is a status flag indicating whether the
attempt to set the value of the variable has succeeded or failed. Note
that you don't really need to use var3Offset (which stores the offset
location of var3) to call the DA_SetInt function. But using variables to
represent the offset values can help you document the members of a data
structure in your code and make your code more readable.

DLLACCES also offers a similar set of DA_Get functions to help you
retrieve the values of data members. For example, to get the value of
var1 (a long integer), you would use DA_GetLong. Again, you supply the
address of the data structure and the offset of the data member (0 in
this case, since var1 is the first member of the data structure):

var1Offset = 0
var1Value = DA_GetLong(lpStruct,

var1Offset)

DA_GetLong locates the data member, translates the data at the memory
location to a long integer, and places the value in var1Value.

Accessing a string member in a data structure is just as easy, but it's
worth a brief discussion. As the example in Figure 2 suggests, the data
in the var4 data member is really only the address of a string: The
actual character data is stored outside the data structure. This format
allows the string to be of any length without requiring you to reserve
space in the structure itself. Fortunately, WordBasic strings also work
in this manner: They use the addresses of the actual data. Thus, getting
the string value of the var4 data member is as simple as getting the
values of other members:

var4Offset = 8
var4Val$ = DA_GetString$(lpStruct,

var4Offset)

One thing to be aware of is that many DLL functions return string results
in the data structure, but the functions do not allocate memory for the
strings themselves. Rather, the functions expect the calling routine to
reserve memory buffers for each string and to assign the memory address
of each buffer to the appropriate data member of the structure.

Before we continue, a note of caution is in order. Accessing DLLs makes
WordBasic both powerful and dangerous. Any actions you initiate through a
DLL take place outside the normal error-trapping facilities of the
WordBasic environment. If you use the DLL incorrectly, you can easily
crash Windows. So save your work often, and to prevent losing any
changes, always save your work before you test your macro. And once your
program is debugged, test it out on several different Windows machines
before releasing it to other users.

ORGANIZING THE MACROS

We can make the whole process of creating and manipulating data
structures much easier by combining the setting up of data structures the
DLL calls into a single WordBasic interface function. In fact, it is
often handy to combine such interface functions and other necessary
routines into a single macro library, which in WordBasic terms is simply
a macro whose sole purpose is to supply routines for use by other macros.
By putting common routines into a macro library, you allow one or more
macros to use the routines without having to copy them over and over.

The new capabilities that we want to add to the FileOpen and FileSaveAs
dialog boxes are organized into three macros. CommLib is a macro library
containing the GetFileDlg$ interface function, which is responsible for
doing all the work in calling COMMDLG file-selection functions, plus a
few convenience routines for handling memory allocation. The other two
macros, NewFileOpen and NewFileSaveAs, are simply replacements for
WordBasic's FileOpen and FileSaveAs commands, respectively. Both of these
macros are relatively simple, because they rely heavily on the functions
in the CommLib macro library.

GetFileDlg$ is the most important function in CommLib. This function's
role is to make COMMDLG's GetOpenFileName, GetSaveFileName, and the data
structure they both use--OPENFILENAME--easier for us to use. By calling
the GetFileDlg$ interface function, macros do not need to be aware of the
messy details of the COMMDLG functions--they only need to pass a few
standard WordBasic strings and numbers to GetFileDlg$.

The syntax for using GetFileDlg$ from other macros is

fname$ = CommLib.GetFileDlg$
(OpenOrSave, dir$, fname$,
filt$, title$, flags)

Note that you use the MacroName.FunctionName (arguments. . .) calling
syntax to call GetFileDlg$ from a macro outside the CommLib macro
library. OpenOrSave indicates which of the COMMDLG functions to use: 0
for GetOpenFileName and 1 for GetSaveFileName. The rest of the arguments
let you access a few of the many members of the OPENFILENAME data
structure. In this particular example, you choose the starting directory
(dir$), the required filename (fname$), the filespec filter (filt$), the
title-bar caption (title$), and the flags that refine the behavior of the
file-selection dialog box (flags). The return value fname$ either
contains the full pathname of the file that the user selected or else
contains an empty string indicating that the user has clicked on the
Cancel button.

Supplying the starting directory and filename to the function is a rather
straightforward process, but setting up the file-type filter string and
defining the flags can be a bit tricky. Each file type is described by
two components: the description and the file pattern. To build the filter
string, you need to concatenate all the component pairs, separating each
component with the pipe character (|). Then store the resultant string in
global memory using BuildLPString--one of the convenience routines in the
CommLib macro library. COMMDLG uses the ASCII NUL (0) character as a
separator for the filter string, but BuildLPString translates the pipe
characters to NUL characters before storing the string in global memory.

The file types used for the File Open dialog box in Figure 1, for
instance, are Contracts (*.cnt), Letters (*.let), Invoices (*.inv), and
All Files (*.*). These result in the filter string

filt$ = "Contracts (*.cnt)|*.cnt
|Letters (*.let)|*.let|Invoices
(*.inv)|*.inv|All Files (*.*)|*.*"

The flags argument refines the behavior of the file-selection dialog
boxes. For example, if you set the OFN_FILEMUSTEXIST flag, COMMDLG will
pop up a warning if the user selects an invalid filename. You can use
other flags in order to prevent the changing of directories, prevent the
selection of existing files, and even allow selection of multiple files.
Each flag is represented by a numeric value, which you must define in
your WordBasic code.

Some of the more useful flags are

OFN_READONLY = 1
OFN_OVERWRITEPROTECT = 2
OFN_NOCHANGEDIR = 8
OFN_SHOWHELP = 16
OFN_MULTISELECT = 512
OFN_PATHMUSTEXIST = 2048
OFN_FILEMUSTEXIST = 4096

To use several flags at the same time, just add the values together. Our
NewFileOpen macro, for instance, uses

flags = OFN_PATHMUSTEXIST +

OFN_FILENMUSTEXIST

to force the user to choose a file that already exists.

GETFILEDLG$ IN DETAIL

Although GetFileDlg$ specifically deals with accessing the
GetOpenFileName and GetSaveFileName functions of COMMDLG, the procedure
it uses is applicable whenever you deal with data structures and DLLs.
The full code listing of the GetFileDlg$ and the other functions in the
CommLib macro library is in DLLACCES.DOC, and the following discussion
will attempt to give you an overview.

If you intend to take advantage of DLL functions, your first step in the
WordBasic macro is to declare those DLL functions used by the routines
(functions and subroutines) in the WordBasic macro. In the case of
CommLib macro library, GetFileDlg$ uses functions in the DLLACCES library
and the COMMDLG library (GetOpenFileName and GetSaveFileName). Windows
API functions and DLL functions are generally described in C or Visual
Basic, but it's not too hard to translate them into WordBasic. The
WordBasic declaration for the GetOpenFileName function, for instance, is

Declare Function GetOpenFileName
Lib "COMMDLG.DLL"(lpofn As Long)
As Integer

This tells WordBasic that GetOpenFileName is a function in the
COMMDLG.DLL DLL library, that it returns an integer, and that it takes a
single long integer argument, which represents the address of an
OPENFILENAME data structure. In general, any argument that is the address
of a data structure must be declared as a long integer. You'll use this
long integer in conjunction with the DLLACCES.DLL functions to access the
individual members of the data structure.

Though not strictly necessary, defining each member variable's address
offset at the head of the interface routine is also a good idea. By doing
this, we not only document the data structure, but we also make the code
more readable when the time comes to set and retrieve the values of the
members. To determine the offsets, take a look at the documentation for
the OPENFILENAME data structure shown in Figure 3. The size (in bytes) of
each variable is noted in parentheses after its name.

The final preparatory step is to allocate a memory block of the proper
size to accommodate those members of the COMMDLG data structure that we
plan to use in our macros. Though it is possible to create a variable of
arbitrary size within WordBasic itself (by defining it as a string
variable), the program sometimes behaves strangely if you directly
manipulate this memory in an attempt to make it look like a data
structure. Therefore, you're much better off managing memory yourself by
using Windows global memory (memory that is available to all Windows
applications) for your data structures.

Working with global memory requires the use of Windows API functions, but
I've written a number of convenience routines (which won't be described
in too much detail here for reasons of space) to help your macros
interface with these functions. The AllocVariable convenience routine
lets you reserve a global-memory block of the size (in bytes) that you
request, BuildLPString allocates global memory for individual string
members of data structures, and FreeVariable releases the global memory
allocated by both functions. All are stored in the CommLib macro library
along with GetFileDlg$.

Unlike programming languages that support data structures, WordBasic
cannot automatically calculate the size of a data structure. So before
you can reserve memory for a data structure, you must first add up the
size of all the data members (in this case, 72 bytes). You then pass this
size to the AllocVariable convenience routine, which returns two values
that describe the global memory to Windows and Windows applications--the
unique memory ID (or handle) for the block, and its actual location in
memory. For example:

lStructSize = 72
hStruct = 0 : lpStruct =

AllocVariable(lStructSize,

hStruct)

After the call to AllocVariable, the variable lpStruct contains the
address (location) of the data structure, while the variable hStruct
contains a unique ID of the memory block. Though both variables refer to
the same chunk of memory, they are used for different purposes. You need
the address in lpStruct in order to access the data structure in global
memory and to pass it as an argument to the DLLACCES and COMMDLG
functions, but you need the handle in hStruct to free up the memory block
(using the FreeVariable convenience function) when you're finished.

One quirk of AllocVariable is that it requires the memory-handle variable
(hStruct, in this case) to exist before you call it, for reasons too
obscure to explain here. The code fragment above reflects this
requirement; it creates hStruct and assigns it a value of 0 before
calling the AllocVariable function.

INITIALIZING THE DATA STRUCTURE

Once these preparatory steps have been completed, the GetFileDlg$
interface function then proceeds to use DLLACCES's DA_Set functions to
initialize those members of the OPENFILENAME structure that we plan to
use as input to COMMDLG's GetOpenFileName and GetSaveFileName functions.
This is the most lengthy and important section of the GetFileDlg$
interface function (see Figure 4). When building your own interface
functions, you'll need to consult the documentation for the DLL to
determine which members you should set before calling the DLL and which
members to examine after calling the DLL.

As we noted above, GetFileDlg$ allows the calling program to specify the
values of just five of the members of OPENFILENAME: the initial
directory, the initial filename, the filespec filter string, the
title-bar caption, and the flags. In addition to transferring these
values to the appropriate places in the data structure, we also need to
set up data members that represent the size of the data structure and the
ID of the active window, as required by the GetOpenFileName and
GetSaveFileName functions. In addition, we also need to preallocate
memory to hold the filename and file title that the COMMDLG functions
will return.

The following code fragment shows how the function sets the first two
members of the OPENFILENAME structure:

r=DA_SetLong(lpStruct,

lStructSizeOff, lStructSize)
hWnd = GetActiveWindow

r=DA_SetInt(lpStruct,

hwndOwnerOff, hWnd)

This routine uses the DLLACCES DA_SetLong function to assign the long
integer value representing the size of the structure (lStructSize) to the
data-structure member at the offset stored in the variable
lStructSizeOff. It then uses DA_SetInt to assign the integer value
representing the handle of the active window hWnd to the member at the
offset stored in the variable hwndOwnerOff.

Handling string members of data structures is somewhat different.
Remember that the data structure stores only the address of a memory
buffer that contains the string, not the string data itself. The
BuildLPString convenience routine is used to reserve buffers in global
memory to hold the contents of each string variable and then assigns the
address of each buffer to the appropriate member of the data structure.

BuildLPString's syntax is similar to AllocVariable's--it returns the
location and the handle of the allocated global-memory block. The
following two lines, for example, are used to initialize the filter
string member of the OPENFILENAME structure by setting it to the string
variable filt$:

hstrFilter = 0 : lpstr =
BuildLPString(filt$, hstrFilter)

r=DA_SetLong(lpStruct,

lpstrFilterOff, lpstr)

BuildLPString builds the string in global memory and then returns the
address (lpstr) and the memory handle (hstrFilter). The DA_SetLong
function initializes the filter string member by using the memory address
of the data structure (lpStruct), the offset of the filter string member
(lpstrFilterOff), and the memory address of the string (lpstr). Note that
you'll use the memory-block handle (hstrFilter) to free up the memory
block when you're finished.

BuildLPString also performs another service: It converts all pipe
characters () in the input string to a NUL character (ASCII 0) before
storing it in global memory. The GetOpenFileName and GetSaveFileName
functions expect each component of the filter to be separated by a NUL
character, but since these are difficult to enter in WordBasic,
BuildString allows the filter input string to use the pipe character
instead.

You can use BuildLPString in conjunction with the WordBasic String$()
command to preallocate memory for string data members that you expect to
receive results from the COMMDLG functions. To reserve memory for the
selected filename, the following lines of code allocate a global-memory
block of at least 256 bytes, assign the memory location to the data
member at the offset stored in lpstrFileOff, and assign the size of the
memory block of the member at the offset stored in nMaxFileOff. (This
prevents the COMMDLG functions from returning strings longer than this
value.)

hstrFile = 0 : lpstrFile =
BuildLPString(fname$ +
String$(256, 0), hstrFile)
r = DA_SetLong(lpStruct,
lpstrFileOff, lpstrFile)
r = DA_SetLong(lpStruct,
nMaxFileOff, 256)

Because this filename data member (at the lpstrFileOff offset) can also
be used as the input to set the initial filename displayed in the
file-selection dialog box, simply add the initial filename fname$ in
front of the 256-byte string buffer--created by the WordBasic
String$(256, 0) function call.

CALLING AND EXITING

Once we've done the complex job of setting up the data structure, calling
the DLL function is almost anticlimactic: We just pass it the address of
the data structure:

If OpenOrSave = 0 Then
success = GetOpenFileName(lpStruct)

Else

success = GetSaveFileName(lpStruct)
End If
If success = 0 Then
Goto Bye
End If

The first argument to GetFileDlg$ is OpenOrSave, which allows the calling
program to choose which of the two COMMDLG file-selection functions
(GetOpenFileName or GetSaveFileName) to call. The selected COMMDLG
function pops up a file-selection dialog box like the one shown in Figure
1 and handles all the user interaction from here on. It stores
information (such as the name of the selected file and the status of the
Read Only checkbox) in members of the data structure before returning a
status. The status is then checked to see whether the call was
successful. If it wasn't, an empty string is returned to the calling
program.

Assuming the call to the COMMDLG function is successful, we can retrieve
the output data from the data structure using the DLLACCES DA_Get
functions. We are interested in only two values for the GetFileDlg$
interface routine: the selected filename and the flags (which are used to
check if the user clicked on the Read Only box).

f$ = DA_GetString$(lpStruct,
lpstrFileOff) flags = DA_GetLong(lpStruct,

FlagsOff)

The f$ string contains the name of the selected file, and flags is the
value of the flags data member.

The final step in the GetFileDlg$ interface function is to free all the
global memory used for the call to the COMMDLG function, including the
global-memory blocks for string variables that were allocated by
BuildLPString. Always free global memory when you no longer need it. If
you don't, Windows will eventually run out of memory, and you'll have to
restart WinWord or Windows.

The FreeVariable convenience routine is a handy way to perform this
necessary function. FreeVariable takes only one argument: the memory
handle of the block that was returned to you by AllocVariable or
BuildLPString. The Bye: label before the FreeVariable calls ensures that
all the memory is freed whenever the execution exits this function via
calls to Goto Bye:.

Bye:

FreeVariable(hTitle)

FreeVariable(hstrFileTitle)

FreeVariable(hstrFile)

FreeVariable(hstrFilter)

FreeVariable(hStruct)

One of the beauties of Word for Windows is configurability. Since all the
menu entries, toolbar buttons, and key assignments invoke WordBasic
commands, you can change the behavior of the program simply by replacing
these commands with your own custom macros. Thus, if we change the name
of the NewFileOpen macro mentioned above to the default name FileOpen,
executing the File Open command (either by clicking on the FileOpen tool
in the toolbar or by choosing File Open from the menu) will run our
replacement macro rather than the default command.

Since most of the work is performed by GetFileDlg$, the NewFileOpen macro
looks very simple (see Figure 5). It supplies the starting directory and
filenames, builds the filter string, specifies the characteristics of the
dialog box, and calls the GetFileDlg$ function with 0 as the first
argument. It then calls the WordBasic FileOpen command to open up the
selected file, choosing the ReadOnly option if GetFileDlg$ returned with
OFN_READONLY set.

The NewFileSaveAs macro is quite similar, except that it tells
GetFileDlg$ to access the COMMDLG function GetSaveFileName instead of
GetOpenFileName, and that it uses the OFN_OVERWRITEPROTECT flag to
prevent the user from inadvertently overwriting an existing file.
(NewFileOpen uses the OFN_FILEMUSTEXIST flag to allow reselection if the
user enters a nonexistent file.)

To try out these macros, start Word for Windows, open the file DLL
ACCES.DOC (included in the DLLACC.ZIP file that you download from PC
MagNet's Programming forum), and double-click on the line that reads
"Double-click here to install the CommLib library." This installs the
CommLib macro library into your global template (NORMAL.DOT), making its
routines available to all your macros. It also copies the DLLACCES.DLL to
your WINDOWS\SYSTEM directory. (You can click on the corresponding
UnInstall sentence to reverse the process.)

Now double-click the sentence, "Double-click here to test New FileOpen."
You should see a file-selection dialog box like the one in Figure 1. Try
typing in a filename that does not exist and click on the OK button. The
COMMDLG function should pop up a warning box and ask you to try again.

To use the NewFileOpen macro as your normal FileOpen command, open the
NewFileOpen macro and copy the contents to your global FileOpen macro.
It's important that you make sure to change the filter string to match
the filespec patterns you wish to have. Copy the contents of the
NewFileSaveAs macro to your global FileSaveAs macro in order to use the
custom file-selection dialog box when you save a file.

CONCLUSION

As you can see, most of the work in calling DLL functions that use data
structures is in setting up the data structure itself--defining the
address offsets and assigning data to the structure members. The DLLACCES
helper functions and the global-memory convenience routines described
here can help out, leaving only simple tasks to be performed by the
command macro itself. With a little imagination, you should be able to
adapt these steps to develop your own interface routines.

When you feel comfortable with this step, you might want to try exploring
the remaining functions in COMMDLG. Each of these functions uses its own
custom data structure, documented in WIN31WH.HLP, the on-line help file
for the Windows 3.1 Software Development Kit. DLLACCES.DOC contains a
short tutorial that should help you convert this information into
WordBasic terms.

If you're on a Novell Network, you can move beyond the COMMDLG functions
and explore the NetWare API (NWNETAPI.DLL) functions. The NetWare API
also makes extensive use of data structures. As a first cut, try calling
the GetServerInformation function. It uses the FILE_SERV_INFO data
structures, which contain, among other items, the server name, the
NetWare version, and the number of connections in use. You can find the
Visual Basic documentation for the NetWare API functions on CompuServe in
the MSBASIC forum, Lib 6, in the file NIVB.ZIP.

This article gives just a glimpse of what you can accomplish when you use
DLLs and data structures. Half the fun is in finding the right DLL
functions to do your bidding. And whenever you must deal with data
structures, you can use the organizational tips presented here to make
DLL access routines more understandable and easier to use.
