Title:     The WordBasic programming language.
             (Tutor)
Author:    Prosise, Jeff


Abstract:  Techniques for using the WordBasic programming language
           included in Microsoft Word for Windows (WinWord) are
           presented. WordBasic is one of the most powerful macro
           languages available; it is modeled after the familiar BASIC
           language and is an extensive application-specific programming
           platform. Microsoft unfortunately does not include full
           documentation for WordBasic in the Word package; users must
           order it separately. WordBasic is easy to learn if the user is
           familiar with structured dialects of BASIC; it uses similar
           syntax, handles variables the same way and supports most
           standard BASIC flow-control statements. The language has many
           statements and functions specific to WinWord. All macros are
           stored internally as WordBasic programs in WinWord, and users
           can create a macro using either a macro recorder or by
           directly editing statements in a window. The macro recorder
           converts users' keystrokes into WordBasic code that can be
           edited. A handful of macro names are reserved for special
           purposes. Sample macros that transpose letters, split the
           WinWord window vertically and change default key assignments
           are included.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Full Text:

Microsoft Word for Windows is one of the most powerful word processors on
the market. It's also one of the most flexible: The basic elements of its
user interface--elements that are cast in stone and hidden deep within
the bowels of most applications--can be modified to suit the needs of
individual users. Want to add a new menu item to the Tools menu? No
problem; just select Tools | Options | Menus and register the new menu
item. Care to change a key assignment or add a new button to the overhead
toolbar? That's no problem, either. In fact, WinWord puts so many
configuration options before you, there's virtually no end to the
remolding and reshaping that you can do.

But perhaps the most remarkable aspect of WinWord is its built-in
programming language, WordBasic. WordBasic is a powerful
application-specific development tool modeled after the BASIC language,
which is familiar to millions of PC users. It's an extensive programming
platform that provides indirect access to the Windows application
programming interface (API) functions and can even be used to effect
Dynamic Data Exchange (DDE). It is also the stuff macros are made of.
Every WinWord macro that you define is stored internally as one or more
WordBasic statements. If you've never used WordBasic, you're missing out
on one of Word for Windows' most potentially useful features.

Unfortunately, the Using WordBasic manual isn't included in the basic
WinWord package but must be ordered separately. The WinWord User's Guide
contains a scant 24 pages of information on WordBasic. As a result, the
majority of WinWord users have never used WordBasic directly. A number of
users probably aren't even aware that it exists. But it's there, and with
it an enterprising user can customize WinWord to his heart's delight and
even write dedicated mini-apps that exist only within the context of his
word processor.

THE BASICS OF WORDBASIC

If you're already familiar with modern (structured) dialects of the BASIC
programming language, then you can easily pick up WordBasic. The syntax
is very much the same. WordBasic supports most of the standard BASIC
flow-control statements (Goto, For-Next, If-Then-Else, Select Case, and
While-Wend), and it handles variables in exactly the same way as BASIC.
The chief difference between BASIC and WordBasic is that the latter
supports many statements and functions specific to WinWord. For example,
the CenterPara command centers a paragraph on the page, and DocSplit
splits the current document window into two panes. In all, WordBasic
supports about 500 different statements and functions. If you don't have
access to a copy of Using WordBasic, you can list all the commands that
WordBasic supports by selecting Help Index from WinWord's Help menu and
clicking WordBasic Programming Language. Click on a command name to get
syntactical help with that command, or click on WordBasic Cross Reference
to display a list of WordBasic command categories. You can also get
context-sensitive help inside the macro-editing window by pressing F1
while the cursor is positioned over a command.

WinWord stores all macros internally as WordBasic programs. There are two
ways to create a macro, and therefore two ways to create a WordBasic
program: by using WinWord's built-in macro recorder to record a series of
mouse and keyboard events, or by opening a macro-editing window and
directly entering the macro statements. To demonstrate the former
technique, select Record Macro from WinWord's Tools menu, enter a macro
name in the Record Macro Name box (or accept the default), and click OK.
With WinWord now recording your every action, type "Hello, world" and
select Stop Recorder from the Tools menu. Then select ToolsMacro,
highlight the macro name in the Macro Name list box, and click Edit.
WinWord's macro-editing window will appear, displaying the following
three program lines:

Sub MAIN
Insert "Hello, world"
End Sub

What happened? WinWord's macro recorder converted your keystrokes into a
WordBasic command that says, "Insert the text 'Hello, world' into the
document at the current cursor position." When you replay this macro,
WinWord will execute the WordBasic program you just created.
Alternatively, you could have created the macro directly by selecting
Tools | Macro, entering the macro name in the Macro Name box, clicking
Edit to display the macro-editing window, and typing Insert "Hello,
world". You can create simple macros using the macro recorder, but to
create complex macros (that can, for example, use conditional logic to
branch to different instructions based on the value of a variable or the
result of an input event) or macros that contain WordBasic commands for
which there are no keyboard, menu, or toolbar equivalents, you'll need
the macro editor.

The best way to get familiar with any programming language is to jump
right in and start writing programs, and WordBasic is no exception.
Limited space prohibits a full treatment of the WordBasic programming
language, but to get you started (and perhaps to get you interested in
learning more about WordBasic), the remainder of this column presents
some useful WordBasic macros designed to solve common problems with
WinWord. To enter these macros, open the macro-editing window as
described above and enter the macro text as shown. To save a macro, close
the macro-editing window by double-clicking the control-menu box in the
window's upper-left corner and answer yes when WinWord asks if you want
to keep the changes. Then when closing WinWord, answer yes when WinWord
asks if you want to save global glossary and command changes. Another way
of saving the macro is to select Save All from WinWord's File menu and
answer yes when WinWord asks you about saving your changes.

WORDBASIC AND THE AUTO MACROS

WinWord reserves a handful of macro names for special purposes. For
example, if a macro is named AutoExec, that macro is automatically
executed whenever WinWord is started. Similarly, the AutoOpen macro is
executed every time a document is opened. Other Auto macros include
AutoNew, which is executed when a new document is created; AutoClose,
which is executed when a document is closed; and AutoExit, which is
executed when WinWord terminates. Combined with a few simple WordBasic
instructions, the Auto macros present some special opportunities for you
to customize WinWord's behavior.

Here's an example. By default, WinWord positions the cursor at the
beginning of a document when an existing document file is opened. You can
return the cursor to the position it was in when the document was last
saved by pressing Shift-F5, which invokes WordBasic's GoBack command. If
you'd prefer that WinWord return the cursor to its previous position by
default, create the macro

Sub Main

GoBack

End Sub

Be sure to name the macro AutoOpen, and save it as a global macro. Then
each time you open a document, WinWord will restore the cursor to its
last position. The only problem with this macro, as Guy Gallo points out
in his excellent book Take WinWord to the Edge (1993, Ziff-Davis Press),
is that it has the odd effect of switching back to the previously active
document when you open a template, rather than a document, for editing.
You can easily solve this problem by modifying the macro to read

Sub Main
If ExistingBookmark("\PrevSel1")
Then EditGoTo "\PrevSel1"
End Sub

When a document is saved, WinWord automatically stores the cursor
position as a bookmark called \PrevSel1. AutoOpen will return to the
previous insertion point only if this bookmark exists in the current
file, a condition that does not hold true for templates.

One use for the AutoExec macro is to make sure that WinWord's main
program window pops up in a certain state. If you terminate WinWord while
it is maximized, it will automatically maximize the next time you start
it. If you terminate WinWord in a windowed (nonmaximized) state, it will
restart in a windowed state. You can ensure that WinWord will always
maximize itself on start-up by creating the following macro and naming it
AutoExec:

Sub Main
If Not AppMaximize()
Then AppMaximize
End Sub

The AppMaximize command doubles as both a statement and a function.
AppMaximize() returns a nonzero value if the WinWord window is maximized.
AppMaximize (without the parentheses) maximizes the window if it's not
maximized or restores it to nonmaximized form if it is already maximized.

The tasks that you can accomplish with WordBasic and the Auto macros are
limited only by your imagination. You could, for example, write AutoExec
and AutoExit macros that use WordBasic's Date$() and Time$() functions to
write a date and time entry to a log file each time WinWord is started or
terminated, or each time a document file is opened or closed.

Like any good programming language, WordBasic supports a full complement
of file I/O functions. You could even write an AutoExec macro that
prompts the user for a user name or a password to restrict access to
WinWord. Lest you rely too heavily on Auto macros for security, however,
be aware that starting WinWord with a /M switch bypasses AutoExec.

TRANSPOSING CHARACTERS

If you're like me, when you scan your word processing documents you
frequently find that in your haste you accidentally reversed two
characters in the middle of a word. The word transpose, for instance, may
become trasnpose. This little problem can be easily corrected by this
macro, which exchanges the character left of the cursor with the
character right of the cursor:

Sub Main
CharLeft 1,1

EditCut

CharRight

EditPaste

CharLeft

End Sub

Before running this macro, position the cursor between the two characters
that you wish to transpose. If you use this macro often, you can use the
Keyboard section of WinWord's Tools | Options menu to assign the macro to
a key combination, menu, or toolbar button. Then you can run it without
having to bring up WinWord's Macro dialog box.

SPLIT WINWORD'S WINDOW VERTICALLY

If you use the Borland C for Windows program editor (part of the Borland
C++ package for DOS and Windows), you, like me, may have grown to love
its Window | Tile command. When invoked with two source-code files open,
Window | Tile splits the document window vertically in half and fills
each half with a source-code window. This is a wonderful arrangement for
comparing two source-code files line for line. WinWord has no comparable
command, though you can split the document window horizontally with
Window | Arrange All.

With WordBasic, you can arrange document windows however you like. The
following macro tiles two documents vertically so that each fills the
entire screen from top to bottom, but only half of the screen
horizontally:

Sub Main
If CountWindows() = 2 Then
xPos = Val(AppInfo$(6)) / 2
yPos = Val(AppInfo$(7))
If DocMaximize()
Then DocMaximize
DocMove 0, 0
DocSize xPos, yPos

NextWindow

DocMove xPos, 0
DocSize xPos, yPos

NextWindow

Else

Beep

MsgBox "There must be exactly
two documents open", "Error", 48
End If
End Sub

The macro only tiles the windows if CountWindows() returns the value 2,
meaning there are exactly two documents open. The active document is
placed on the left, the inactive one on the right. If more or fewer than
two documents are open, the MsgBox statement displays an error message.
This macro calls DocMaximize to nonmaximize the active document window if
it is currently maximized, because neither DocMove nor DocSize will work
on a maximized window. AppInfo$(6) and AppInfo$(7) return the width and
height of the active document workspace, respectively.

CHANGING DEFAULT KEY ASSIGNMENTS

Through the Options dialog box invoked with the Tools | Options command,
WinWord lets you assign macros and WordBasic commands to individual keys
and key combinations. This makes it possible to change the default
actions initiated by the A to Z, 0 to 9, F2 to F12, Ins, and Del
keys--alone or in combination with the Ctrl or Ctrl and Shift keys. With
this remapping capability and a helping hand from WordBasic, you can add
some interesting twists to WinWord's keyboard interface. For example, the
following macro, when assigned to the Ins key, causes WinWord to emit a
beep whenever you press the Ins key to switch between insert and
overstrike modes (a handy feature if you hit Ins by accident and don't
realize you're in overstrike mode until you've overtyped a line of text):

Sub Main

Beep

Overtype

End Sub

WinWord's Options dialog box offers only a limited selection of keys, but
you can reprogram virtually any key on the keyboard using WordBasic's
ToolsOptionsKeyboard command. The following WordBasic macro programs the
Alt-Spacebar key combination to execute a macro named DoCalc.
(Alt-Spacebar normally displays the system menu.)

Sub Main
ToolsOptionsKeyboard .Name="DoCalc",
.KeyCode=1056, .Context=0
Print "Alt-Spacebar is now enabled"
End Sub

The value 1056 for the .KeyCode value is derived from a table in the Help
for the ToolsOptionsKeyboard command. DoCalc, in turn, is defined

Declare Function IsAppLoaded
Lib "Kernel"(Name$)\
As Integer Alias "GetModuleHandle"

Sub MAIN
If IsAppLoaded("Calc") Then
AppActivate "Calculator"

Else

Shell "CALC.EXE", 1
End If
End Sub

After the first of these macros is executed, pressing Alt-Spacebar
executes DoCalc, which brings up the Windows Calc accessory. If Calc
isn't already loaded somewhere in the system, DoCalc launches Calc with a
Shell command. If Calc is already loaded, DoCalc simply brings Calc to
the foreground by calling AppActivate and passing it Calc's window title.
Among other things, DoCalc illustrates how WordBasic programs can
directly access Windows API functions. In this case, IsAppLoaded invokes
Windows' native GetModuleHandle function, which accepts a module
(program) name and returns a module handle if a module of that name is
active in the system. A return value of 0 means the module is not loaded.

One of the most inventive uses for WordBasic key remapping that I've ever
seen is embodied in the SmartQuotes macro supplied with WinWord (in the
document file NEWMACRO.DOC). SmartQuotes is actually four macros in one.
AutoEnableSmartQuotes reprograms the keyboard to execute
AutoInsertSingleQuote when the Apostrophe key is pressed and
AutoInsertDoubleQuote when the Shift and Apostrophe keys are pressed
together. These AutoInsertQuote macros replace the standard
typewriter-style single and double quotation marks with publisher-style
curled quotation marks as you type. The fourth macro,
AutoDisableSmartQuotes, restores normal operation.

WRAPPING UP

To close, here's a favorite WordBasic macro of mine that inserts today's
date into a WinWord document:

Sub Main
InsertDateTime .DateTimePic = "MMMM d, yyyy"

CharLeft

UnlinkFields

CharRight

End Sub

Of course, inserting a date using WinWord's Insert | Date and Time
command is easy enough. But dates inserted with Insert | Date and Time
are inserted as fields, which is inappropriate if all you need is, say, a
date at the top of a business letter. This macro inserts a field
containing today's date in the format August 23, 1993, and then converts
the field into static text. Now you don't have to worry about the date at
the top of the letter changing if you decide to update other fields in
the document.

Needless to say, this discussion only scratches the surface of what you
can do with WordBasic. If you would like more information, you can order
Using WordBasic from Microsoft. You'll find instructions for ordering in
your WinWord package. As an alternative, you can call Microsoft Sales and
Service at 800-426-9400. You may also find it helpful to pick up a good
book on the subject. Two of my favorites are Take WinWord to the Edge
(1993, Ziff-Davis Press) and Woody Leonhard and Vincent Chen's Hacker's
Guide to WinWord (1993, Addison-Wesley Publishing Company).

Take some time to explore WordBasic, and you'll open up a whole new
universe of possibilities for customizing the WinWord environment.
