Title:     Quick tips.
Author:    Rohan, Rebecca


Abstract:  Tips for using several popular microcomputer applications,
           including Microsoft Word for Windows and OnTime for Windows,
           are presented. OnTime users can print out all messages in the
           system but can only view messages for a single day on the
           screen; those who have a print-to-disk driver installed can
           display reports on-screen. Changing the default .DOC extension
           in Microsoft Word for Windows 2.0 involves adding a single
           line to the WIN.INI file. One way to calculate columns in Word
           for Windows without using tables is to select a column with
           the Ctrl-Shift-F8 key combination and choose Calculate from
           the Tools menu; the result of the calculation will appear on
           the status bar. The bombing of the World Trade Center should
           make users more aware of the need for off-site backups for
           disaster recovery.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Full Text:

Tip 1: See OnTime Reports Onscreen

If you have a program like OnTime for Windows that relies heavily on
printer output, you might want to get more information from the screen
before firing up your printer. With OnTime, you can print out all
messages in the system, but are only able to view messages for a single
day on the screen. This omission can be particularly annoying for those
who have no printer. If you have a program like ZSoft's Publisher's
Paintbrush with a driver for printing to TIFF files on-disk, you can now
view all your messages without a printer.

Make sure the print-to-disk driver is installed in Windows. If it is,
you'll see it when you enter Printer Setup from a program's File menu, or
from the Printers icon in Windows' Control Panel. When you want to see
all messages in OnTime, use Printer Setup to switch to the Print-to-TIFF
driver, then choose "Print all messages in system" from the File menu's
Print selection. When the output is written to disk, open Publisher's
Paintbrush and view your appointments as a TIFF file.

TIP 2: Change the Default DOC Extension in WinWord 2.0

If WinWord's DOC extensions are too generic, add this line your WIN.INI
under the section with the bracketed [Microsoft Word 2.0] heading:
DOC-extension=.bob (or the extension you use most often).

Now, when you use the Open command from the File menu, WinWord will offer
a list of files with your chosen extension. The default extension for
saved files will also change.

By changing the document extension once a month to J93 (for January
1993), F93, M93, etc., you'll see only a list of files created during the
current month when you use the Open command from the File menu. Use the
extensions JAN, FEB, MAR, etc. to get a list of all the January files
from every year you use the new extension conventions. If your work is
cyclical, it may pay to go to File Manager and sort old files by date,
renaming them to fit a new monthly or quarterly model.

TIP 3: Green Pictures in WinWord?

If you use the Insert menu to import a large BMP (bitmap) file to
WinWord, the picture may look green in places. To correct that, try using
the Paste command from the Edit menu. With Paste, the same picture should
appear perfectly normal.

Tip 4: Calculate Without Tables in WinWord 2.0

You don't have to insert a table or even separate columns with tabs to
select columns of numbers in WinWord 2.0 as long as you use the keyboard
instead of the mouse. First, make sure the status bar is displayed by
choosing Options from the Tool menu. Click the View icon and see that
Status Bar is checked.

To select a column, place the cursor at one corner of the column of
numbers you want to calculate. Press Control, Shift, and F8. "COL"
appears on the status bar. Use arrow keys to select the rest of the
column, then choose Calculate from the Tools menu. The result of the
calculation appears on the status bar.

Tip 5: Keeping and Flushing Clips

After copying and pasting large graphics or blocks of text, save the file
that received the pasted object, and then bring up the Windows Clipboard.
To flush the contents of the Clipboard, choose Edit, and then Delete.

When Delete is selected, a dialog box will ask if you want to clear the
contents of the clipboard. You may also save clips for future use with a
CLP extension.

Tip 6: Lesson From the Trade Center

After the catastrophe at the World Trade Center, it should be clear that
it isn't enough to make backups of files. If your business depends on the
data you keep, it's important to have a second set of backups stored
off-site.

Professional off-site storage services abound, but small businesses with
information that isn't highly confidential might get by with storing a
set of backups at home in case of fire or flood.

To guard against widespread perils such as earthquakes, consider
exchanging data with an out-of-town branch. Single-site business owners
from opposite sides of town might cooperatively store backups for each
other. Two business owners could install dedicated backup hard drives on
each other's machines, then dial into their off-site vaults to perform a
second backup at the close of the business day.

Choose a backup partner from contacts made at trade associations or civic
groups. Use DES file encryption to keep files confidential. Be
far-sighted with disaster-planning--and creative with low-hassle
solutions. If you'd rather not tie up phone lines, choose a partner whose
office is across town from yours, but on the way home from work, then
drop off backups after you leave your office.

If you back up to a tape drive, have an identical drive with identical
tape-drive software installed on your backup buddy's machine so you can
get to your files if disaster strikes. Meet with your new partner to
discuss hardware and software purchases. The more identical hardware and
software you buy, the easier it would be to work in your partner's
environment if your office is unavailable. Discuss ways you could share
space and equipment in a worst-case scenario. Can you take over your
partner's office at night?

Think through all aspects of your business that can't be saved by renting
new office space and equipment. If you depend on paper files, now is the
time to scan and store that data off-site. Make it office policy to store
every address and phone number on both electronic and paper media. That
way, current records can be easily backed up across town over the phone
lines, and you'll have access to the paper records in case of a power
failure.

Tip 7: Cheap Reminder

If you open Windows with a command in your AUTOEXEC.BAT file, and close
Windows at the end of your workday, it's easy to give yourself a free
reminder to back up files, pick up the kids, take backups home, and so
on. Add this line to your AUTOEXEC.BAT file, right after the line that
reads "WIN": @ECHO Take floppies home!

The reminder will only appear the first time you quit Windows after each
boot of the machine.
