Full Text:

Take it from the experts: There is an easier way. Streamline your work
with these 67 timesavers for 16 best-selling DOS and Windows
applications.

Software is supposed to make our lives easier. But today's mainstream
applications give you so many ways to accomplish the same thing, you may
end up taking the long road home when the shortcut is just a keystroke or
mouse click away.

To identify the shortcuts, we asked 16 software gurus, book authors,
support technicians, consultants, and PC World contributing editors to
let us in on their secrets for the quickest, most efficient ways to
operate inside their favorite applications. You'll find hot tips for
using best- selling word processors (Ami Pro 3.0, WordPerfect 5.1,
WordPerfect 5.1 for Windows, Microsoft Word 5.0 and 5.5, and Word for
Windows 2.0); spreadsheet programs (1-2-3 for DOS and Windows, Quattro
Pro for DOS, and Excel 4.0); databases (dBASE IV and Paradox); draw,
presentation, and desktop publishing packages (CorelDraw 3.0, Harvard
Graphics 3.0, and PageMaker 4.0); and even the enormously popular
accounting program Quicken 6.0. Whether you use just one or several of
these packages, you'll find tips that will make you so much more
productive, you may be able to leave work an hour early.

Working Smart in Ami Pro 3.0

Working in Style

In the old days of DOS word processors, I did a lot of manual formatting.
Now I create specialized templates for common documents, so when I need a
bulleted list or an indented paragraph, I just press a function key or
pick a style from a list. Here's how you can set up customized style
sheets.

Start Ami Pro, which loads the -DEFAULT.STY sheet and selects
Style-Modify Style. From the Style list, choose Body Text for the bulk of
your text. Specify the font, size, alignment, and other options in the
dialog box, then select Save. Modify the other existing styles in the
same way. To create a new style name, such as Indented Text, choose Body
Text, select Save As, type the new name, then select OK. Select the
Alignment option and set your indents, then make any other changes you
need and select Save again. Create or alter any other styles you need,
then select OK. To alter page layout options for the default template,
select Page- Modify Page Layout and set up margins, columns, tabs, and so
on.

To make your changes permanent, select Style-Save as a Style Sheet. In
the dialog box, type -DEFAULT.STY in the File Name text box if it's not
already there. Enter a description in the Description text box, then
select OK and confirm overwriting the file. For other types of documents,
follow the same steps, but enter a different file name when you save the
style sheet.

Stylish Templates

Style sheets aren't limited to formatting; they can also contain
boilerplate text, frames, and graphical images. I've created a
letterhead, with my company logo, as part of a LETTER.STY style sheet.
Type in a signature block and add an automatically updated date by
selecting Edit-Insert-Date- Time. Just add the standard elements before
saving your document as a style sheet. Then, in the Save as a Style Sheet
dialog box, check the With Contents box before selecting OK.

Paragraph Pranks

To attach a template to a new document, select File-New, choose that
template from the list, and select OK. You'll save time if you type your
text in the default Body Text style. To reformat, position the cursor in
the paragraph, then click the Style button on the left side of the status
bar at the bottom of the screen to display a list. It's even faster to
press the function key shown to the left of each style in the list. To
change the function keys, select Style-Style Management and make your
changes in the dialog box.

For even faster paragraph formatting, assign a style to one block of
text, then select that block and press <Ctrl>-T or select Text-Fast
Format. Choose Only Paragraph Style and select OK. Your mouse pointer
will change to a paintbrush. To apply the same style to other paragraphs,
click and drag on any part of a paragraph. When you're finished with that
particular style, press <Ctrl>-T or select Text-Fast Format again to turn
fast formatting off.

-George Campbell

Working Smart in Word 5.0

Quick Keystrokes

I'm neither a menu person nor a mouser. Fortunately, Word 5.0 supports my
style with some handy keystrokes, such as <Ctrl>-<Page Up> to get to the
first line of a document, and <Ctrl>-<Page Down> to reach the end.

To select a paragraph, place the cursor anywhere in the paragraph and
press <F10>. To format continuous text, press <F6> at the start of the
text, then press <F10> for as many paragraphs as you want to format, or
use the <Down> and <Right> cursor keys to move quickly through the
document. To apply a format to an entire document, press <Shift>-<F10> to
select all the text, then <Alt>-XB for bold, <Alt>-XU for underline, or
<Alt>-XI for italics.

To undo character formatting, highlight the text, then press <Alt>-X
<Space>. If the paragraph formatting is wrong but you can't figure out
why, select the offending paragraphs, then press <Alt>-XP to strip out
the character or paragraph formatting.

Default Zone

If you hate having your margins set at Word's default 1.25 inches every
time you start a document, don't agonize- customize! Create a style sheet
by pressing <Esc>GI. Then <Tab> to Usage and press D<Tab><F1><Enter>. Now
press FM. Reset the margins to your preferred default and press <Enter>.
Press TS and save the style sheet as the default NORMAL.STY, then press
<Enter>, and E to return to your document.

Zig-Zag Zap

Don't waste time printing documents to see how lines will break. Instead,
press <Esc>O, then tab over to Show Line Breaks and set it to Yes. This
setting will show you where a line of monospace characters will break. If
you see that your text is running off the side of the screen, but you're
not trying to align text, set Show Line Breaks to No.

Working Smart in Word 5.5

Cure for Function Key Homesickness

Because Word 5.5's drop-down menu interface is so handy, I don't have to
remember so many different commands. I do have to remember, though, that
the old <Alt>-key formatting commands from Word 5.0 use the <Ctrl> key
instead. So instead of pressing <Alt>-B for boldface, I have to press
<Ctrl>-B.

Sometimes I get homesick for Word 5.0's function key shortcuts. When this
happens, I select Utilities-Customize, check the Use Word 5.0 Function
Keys box, and select OK.

See It All

To see as much text as possible on the screen, select View- Preferences,
then choose Text, 50 Lines, 80 Columns, 16 Colors in the Display Mode
list box. The Text mode speeds up the program; to see italics and
boldfacing press <Alt>-<F9>.

The Glossary Gift

Whenever I need to store text for use in other documents, I automate the
process with Word's Glossary feature. Here's how: Type the text, then
highlight it and select Edit- Glossary. In the dialog box, type an
easy-to-remember abbreviation (like ADD for an address) in the Glossary
Name field, then select Define. When you exit the program, click Yes to
save glossary changes. When you need the text in another document, type
the abbreviation, then press <F3> to insert it at the cursor position.

If you forget the abbreviations, select Edit-Glossary, find the
abbreviation in the list, and select Insert to pop it in.

Working Smart in Word for Windows 2.0

Cunning Keyboard Tricks

Sometimes there's such a thing as too much freedom of choice. Take
selecting text in WinWord: You can use the mouse, the keyboard, or the
mouse and the keyboard. So what's the fastest, smartest way? Treat the
mouse like the disease-bearing vermin it is and memorize the following
shortcuts.

To select a single word and the space after it, place your cursor on it
and press <F8> twice. To select a sentence and the space after it, press
it three times. Pressing <F8> and a character highlights to the next
occurrence of that character. Four presses gives you the paragraph, and
five selects the whole document. (If you want to get technical, though,
<Ctrl>-<Numpad 5> is an even faster way to select everything.)

Selected more than you wanted? <Shift>-<F8> backs you down one level. If
you change your mind entirely, press <Esc> to turn off WinWord's
selection mode.

Take Control of Your Formats

When you need to format text, take Control. <Ctrl>-B makes selected text
boldface; <Ctrl>-I, italic; <Ctrl>-U, underlined. You can use these
toggles to format selected text or to set the format for the next
character as you type. Press the same key combo to toggle them off.

<Ctrl>-A toggles text entered in lowercase between uppercase or
lowercase, but remember, it's only an appearance; Edit- Find and
Edit-Replace won't see those characters as uppercase, and if you save the
file as text only, you'll lose the appearance formatting. To actually
change the case of selected text, use <Shift>-<F3>, which cycles selected
text through lowercase, uppercase, and initial capitals.

To format paragraphs, press <Ctrl>-1 or <Ctrl>-2 for single and double
spacing, respectively, and <Ctrl>-E, <Ctrl>-L, and <Ctrl>-R for centered,
left-, and right-aligned text. To clear all formatting, press <Ctrl>-
<Space>.

Quick Text Inserts

Only a dolt types the same text more than once. When you need to insert
the same text over and over in your document, save it as a glossary
entry. Select the text, press <Alt>EO to call up the Glossary dialog box,
type a name for the entry (use something memorable), and press <Enter>.
Then, whenever you need to insert the text, type the glossary name and
press <F3>.

The Mouse House

If you must mouse, here are a few pointers. Double-click on a word to
select it. To select a line, place the cursor in the left margin so it
changes from an I-beam to an arrow and click once; to highlight a
paragraph, double-click in the left margin. <Ctrl>-click in text to
select that sentence. To select a longer block of text, click once in the
left margin at the top of the block, hold down <Shift>, and click once at
the bottom. To highlight the whole megillah, <Ctrl>- click in the left
margin. And to select columns, click and drag with the right mouse
button.

Customizing the Tool Bar

Customize your tool bar correctly, and you may never have to pull down a
menu again. Select <Alt>OOT to get to the Toolbar Options dialog box.
Here you can assign an icon to any command or macro in WinWord's arsenal
and place it on the tool bar. Simply click Commands or Macros in the Show
box, scroll down the list of commands or macros, click on the one you
want to add, scroll through the Button list box, and pick an appropriate
icon. In the Tool to Change list box, choose an icon you want to replace
or choose a [space], put the new icon on an empty space on the bar. Click
Change- Close and the new button will appear.

So which icons should you add to your tool bar? Here are five I can't
live without: ViewZoom, which lets me shrink and expand my document view;
DocumentStatistics, for an instant word and character count, as well as
info on editing time and revisions; ControlRun, which takes me to the
Windows Clipboard or Control Panel; ViewPage, for instant print previews;
and InsertPageNumbers, for-well, you can probably figure it out.

Working Smart in WordPerfect 5.1

Key Consciousness

WordPerfect runs fastest with function keys, which are easier to learn if
you lay the program's template on your keyboard and stick the color-coded
decals on the <Ctrl>, <Alt>, and <Shift> keys. I also find it easier to
memorize WordPerfect's commands by using the menus' mnemonic letter
choices.

WordPerfect was designed around the <Home>, <End>, and cursor keys on the
numeric keypad. If you turn off Num Lock and use the numeric keypad
rather than the inverted-T cursor keys, you'll save your fingers a lot of
labor. Also, train yourself to use <Ctrl>-<Right> and <Ctrl>-<Left>,
which move you forward and backward one word at a time, and <Gray Plus>
and <Gray Minus> keys on the numeric keypad, which move you forward and
backward one screen at a time.

Cursor Control

Another set of navigation shortcuts uses the <Home> key to bolster the
effect of the cursor keys. The more often you hit <Home>, the more
extreme the effect: <Home><Up> moves the cursor to the top of the screen;
<Ctrl>-<Home><Up> to the top of the current page; <Home><Home><Up> to the
top of the document; and <Home><Home> <Home><Up> to the top of the
document before any hidden codes. Similarly, <Home><Left> moves to the
left of the screen; <Home><Home><Left> to the beginning of the line (if
you're using a small font or wide paper, a line may be several screens
wide); and <Home><Home><Home><Left> to the beginning of the line before
any codes. (<Down> and <Right> use the same key combos, but it's faster
to use <End> than <Home> <Home><Right>.)

You can move the cursor to a specific page in a document by pressing Go
To (<Ctrl>-<Home>) and entering a page number. Pressing <Ctrl>-<Home>
twice returns you to where you last entered a major navigation command.
To move around when editing, use <Search> (<F2>) to jump to exactly the
right spot: Press <Search>, type the text that appears before the letter
you want the cursor to land on, and press <Search> again.

Around the Block

When you cut a block, WordPerfect tells you to 'Move cursor; press Enter
to retrieve'. If it makes more sense to clean up around the cut before
moving elsewhere to paste, press <F1> (Cancel). The prompt goes away and
you can edit freely. So long as you don't use the Copy or Move commands,
the cut text is still in memory; to retrieve it, position the cursor and
press <Ctrl>-<F4>RB.

For block moves, the time-honored trick in the WordPerfect bag is using
Undo (<F1>). Delete the text you want to move, position the cursor where
you want to paste it, and press <F1>R (Undoo Restore).

Delete Delight

To delete a single word, position the cursor anywhere on it and press
<Ctrl>-<Backspace>; press it repeatedly to delete additional words. To
delete to the end of a line, press <Ctrl>-<End>; continue to hold down
these keys to quickly delete to the end of the current paragraph.

Quick-Change Formats

If you apply a format like Italics from the Font-Appearance menu,
WordPerfect inserts hidden start and end codes: [ITALC] and [italc]. You
don't have to go back to the menu to turn off the format when typing; the
characters you type subsequently are inserted between the codes. Press
<Right> to move past the end code.

-Robert Lauriston

Working Smart in WordPerfect 5.1 for Windows

Keyboard Cut-Ups

I believe in equal rights, so I use a mouse for some things and a
keyboard for others. The mouse is great for clicking on the Button Bar or
selecting text (to select a word, place the cursor on it and
double-click; click three times to select a sentence, four times to
select a paragraph). But memorize the following few keystrokes, and
you'll be racing through your documents faster than the favorite at
Churchill Downs.

To go to the beginning of a document, press <Ctrl>-<Home>; to get to the
end, press <Ctrl>-<End>. Pressing <Ctrl>- <Delete> deletes text to the
end of a line; <Ctrl>- <Backspace> deletes a word. Press <Ctrl>-G<Tab>
<Tab> <Enter> if you want to return the cursor to the last position you
moved it to using a feature such as GoTo, Replace or Home.

Most of us know the time-honored shortcuts, like <Ctrl>-Z for undo, <Ctrl
>-X for cut, <Ctrl>-C for copy, and <Ctrl>-V for paste. Not everyone
knows, though, that pressing <Ctrl>- P will print the document that's on
screen without asking you to fill out a dialog box. Want to extend
highlighting to a certain character? Just press <F8> and type the
character. Want to turn boldface text (or some other different format)
back to normal? Just select it and press <Ctrl>-N to return to normal
text. And press <Ctrl>-W to access special symbols such as foreign
characters and accent marks.

No More Dialog Dallying

Using a mouse to make selections in a dialog box is like shooting peas
with a cannon. Instead, wend your way through dialog boxes by pressing
<Tab> or by holding down <Alt> and pressing the underlined letter of the
area or button you want. To open a pop-up list, move to the list button
and press <Alt>-<Down> or <Alt>-<Up>. Type the underlined letter in an
item's name to move directly to it. And although you can move to a check
box and press <Space> to check or uncheck it, and you can move to a radio
button list and use <Up> or <Down> to make your selection, in both cases,
using <Alt>underlined letter is faster.

Quick Lists

To avoid wasting time searching through file names, I always set up a
Quick List of files and directories. Select File- Open, check the Quick
List box if necessary, select Edit- Quick List and then add the documents
and directories you use most often. (To switch between a Quick List and
the regular directory list in the File Open Dialog Box, press <Alt>-Q to
check and uncheck the Quick List box.)

A Better View

WordPerfect for Windows' Viewer window shows you what's in a file without
actually opening it. Choose File-Open, select the file name, and then
click the View button or press <Alt>-V for a sneak preview. To see what's
in another file in the directory, click it or cursor to it.

Macro Magic

WordPerfect for Windows lets you use your favorite macros with the click
of a button. Once you've recorded a series of commands as a macro and
named it, place it on the Button Bar where you can get to it quickly:
Select View-ButtonBarSetup- Edit, select Assign Macro to Button, choose
the macro from the list, click Assign and voila! The macro shows up on
the button bar. When you're finished adding macros, click OK.

Working Smart in 1-2-3

Release 2.x and 3.x

Make an End of It

If I could see all 8192 rows by 256 columns in my 1-2-3 spreadsheets, I'd
be looking at a screen more than 7 yards wide and 61 yards long. With so
much spreadsheet real estate at hand, it's worthwhile knowing how to get
around.

I use the <End> key to jump almost anywhere in my spreadsheet with
lightning speed. For example, press <End>- <Home>, and the cell pointer
jumps to the bottom right corner of the active worksheet. (If that cell
happens to be cell K50, you can be sure there are no entries or
formatting in any of the cells in columns L through IV and in rows 51
through 8192.) Press <End>-<Right> starting on a blank cell, and the cell
pointer stops at the next nonblank cell to the right of that cell. If
there are no nonblank cells, it shoots all the way to column IV. (If you
start on a nonblank cell, the cell pointer stops at the last nonblank
cell in that series.)

The <End> key works the same way with the other cursor keys, and that
makes finding the beginning and end of data series remarkably fast and
easy. (Note: Using <End> plus the cursor keys is a good way to check
whether a row or column is empty before you delete it.)

You can also review your spreadsheet one screen at a time, if you like,
vertically or horizontally. Vertical is easy: Use <Page Up> and <Page
Down>. Press <Ctrl>-<Left> or <Ctrl>-<Right> to move the cursor a
screenful to the left or right for a horizontal view.

Forming Formulas

Once you master navigation in spreadsheet land, you can use those skills
to build mathematical formulas. When entering a formula that calls for a
range argument, you can select the range in the spreadsheet to enter it
automatically. For example, if you type SUM(, you can then press the
cursor keys to move the cell pointer to the top of a column of values.
Press the period key to anchor the range. Then press <End>-<Down> to
select the whole column of values for summation. To finish, type the
closing parenthesis and press <Enter>.

Slash and Print

To print a fast draft of your spreadsheet, use the /Print command. You
won't get any formatting or graphics, but /Print prints much faster than
the :Print command in 1-2-3's Wysiwyg add-in.

When using Wysiwyg, know thy printer driver. If you're printing draft
copies of graphics or ranges with lots of formatting, choose a driver
that prints at medium or low resolution-between 75 and 150 dots per inch
(dpi). For better quality, try a 300-dpi driver like the HPLASR4 or the
XHPLJ2C driver. (The XHPLJ2C driver is generally faster because it
downloads fonts, while the HPLASR4 does not.) To switch between available
drivers while using release 2.4, choose the :Print-Config-Printer
command. In release 3.1+, select :Print-Configuration-Resolution-Draft.

If you need to print many reports but don't want to wait around, try
printing to encoded files and then printing the files later. Create an
encoded file by selecting /Print- Encoded. To print to an encoded file,
select :Print-File and enter a file name with ENC as the extension (say,
92END1.ENC). After you've created an ENC file, you can print it by typing
COPY /B filename.ENC PRN at the DOS prompt. The resulting report looks
exactly like one printed from within 1-2-3, complete with fancy
formatting and graphics. You can even use wild cards to print multiple
ENC files: For example, type COPY /B *.ENC PRN at the DOS prompt to print
all the ENC files in the current directory.

Working Smart in 1-2-3 for Windows

Get Smart

Talk about choice: If you're used to DOS versions of 1-2-3, you can
always press the slash key to go to the 1-2-3 Classic menu. Pressing the
colon key even displays the Wysiwyg formatting menu. But hey, you're in
Windows. Why not do yourself a favor by using SmartIcons and other
features unique to the Windows version?

The SmartIcon palette is a veritable warehouse of shortcuts you can
customize to fit your way of working. To customize your SmartIcons,
choose Tools-SmartIcons and click the Customize button. You'll see the
current SmartIcon palette in a list box next to a Standard icons list
box. Scroll through the latter list, click on an icon, and you get a
description of the function in the Description box below it. If you find
an icon you like, double-click it to add it to your current palette. (A
few of my favorite SmartIcons are Cycle through colors for backgrounds,
Copy current cell into selected cells, Insert rows, and Insert columns.)
To make room for your new icons, jump over to the Current palette box and
double-click the icons you don't want. When you're satisfied with your
new palette, click OK to save it.

Cell Block

Chances are, you issue a command like Style-Font and then select the
range of cells to which it applies. But if you select a range before you
issue a command, the selection remains active after the command is
executed, making it easier to perform another operation on the same
range.

Help Where You're At

Here's an easy way to get help with @functions. When you need to enter an
@function, press @ and then <F3> for a list of all functions. Press <F1>
for the @Function Index. (You can follow a similar procedure when
entering macro commands. Enter a left brace { and press <F3> for a list
of all macro commands. <F1> displays the Macro Command Index.)

Peace Be Undo You

If you've blown it, you can back out with the Undo command. (First select
Tools-User Setup and make sure Enable Edit Undo is checked.) Issue the
Undo command by selecting Edit- Undo (or pressing <Alt>-<Backspace>). If
you select Undo after executing a macro, your worksheet will be restored
to its previous condition.

Working Smart in Excel 4.0

Be a Copycat

What's the best way to save time building spreadsheets? Build something
once and copy it. With Excel, I enter multiple copies of a formula or a
value in a single step: First, I select the range(s) where I want the
copies to go (holding down <Ctrl> and using the mouse to select multiple
blocks of cells); then I build my first formula and press <Ctrl>-<Enter>.
Every cell in the selection gets a copy.

To copy a formula or row of formulas to lower cells, select that formula
or row and the target range, then press <Ctrl>- D. To copy a formula or
column of formulas to cells to the right, select that formula or column
and the target range, then press <Ctrl>-R.

And how about AutoFill? Sure, you can use it to create a series of
entries, such as days of the week. But I also copy formulas with it: I
enter the first formula, then use the mouse to drag the AutoFill handle
to cover the range that needs copies. If AutoFill makes a series when I
just want to make copies, I hold down <Ctrl> as I drag the AutoFill
handle, and I always get straight copies. Hold down <Shift> as you drag
the AutoFill handle and you'll insert blank cells, shifting adjacent
cells down or to the right.

The drag-and-drop feature lets you select and move a cell, range, row,
column, or graphics object, but hold down <Ctrl> while you drag, and
you'll drag a copy of the cell or object.

When you need to duplicate just the formatting from one range to another,
select the range, then click the Copy tool on the standard tool bar. Now
select the range to be formatted and click on the Paste Formats tool. If
you're copying a set of formulas but need to convert them to values, use
the Copy tool to make your copy, but instead of selecting Edit-Paste
Special-Values, just hold down <Shift> and click the Paste Formats tool.

You're Selected

When it comes to selecting ranges in a spreadsheet, the mouse is a pretty
blunt instrument. Instead, hold down <Shift> and use the cursor keys to
extend the range selection. The selection extends away from the active
cell. Press <Ctrl>-<Period>, to switch the active cell to each corner of
the selection, changing the extensible corner of the range. I use this
trick to adjust the corners of a selected range without canceling the
selection and starting over.

When the range is large, start on one corner, hold down <Shift><End>, and
then press a cursor key: The selection extends to the last filled cell in
that direction.

Try putting the cell pointer in a block of entries and pressing <Ctrl>
<Asterisk>. Excel selects the current block based on a pattern of
adjacent filled cells. If it guessed wrong, hold down <Shift> and use the
cursor keys and <Ctrl>- <Period> to adjust the selection.

Formula Wrestling

When formulas get complex, it can be hard to figure out how they work.
Checking the value of parts of a formula can help. Select the cell that
contains the formula, and press <F2> to edit it. Use the mouse (or <Shift
> plus the cursor keys) to select an expression, then press <F9>. Excel
calculates just that portion of the formula and converts it to a value.
Then select a more inclusive expression and repeat the process to
understand how the formula was built. (Be sure not to enter the converted
formula.)

To analyze formulas on a broader scale, try pressing <Ctrl>` (the reverse
apostrophe key is to the left of 1 key) to toggle between viewing the
values of your formulas (the normal way of looking at a spreadsheet) and
viewing the formulas themselves. If you select Window-New Window and then
press <Ctrl>`, you can compare formulas and their values side by side.
Now, select Options-Workspace, check the Info Window check box in the
Workspace Options dialog box, and click OK to see a window showing
characteristics of the active cell. Press <Alt>I to access the Info menu,
and choose the information you want, such as Precedents (the cells a
formula refers to) and Dependents (cells that contain formulas that refer
to the current cell). Now arrange your spreadsheet and Info windows so
you can see them together on screen, and you're ready to take a very
close look at your spreadsheet formulas.

Working Smart in Quattro Pro 4.0

Keyboard Clues

In some ways, DOS heavyweight Quattro Pro feels like a Windows program.
It provides 12 ways to do the same thing, such as letting me mouse around
or use the keyboard to select commands. For my taste, though, the
keyboard is faster than the mouse for selecting a block of cells.

For example, I like to select an entire current column of data (when the
cell selector is not on the top cell) by pressing <End><Up><Shift>-<F7>
<End><Down>. To select the entire current row of data when the cell
selector is not at the left edge of that data, I press <End><Left><Shift
>- <F7><End><Right>. When the cell selector isn't in the top row or left
column of the block, I select the area by pressing <End><Up><End><Left>,
then <Shift>- <F7><End><Down><End><Right>. To select the entire active
spreadsheet area, from cell A1 to the last cell that contains data, I
press <Home><Shift>-<F7><End><Home>.

Formula and Function

It's a pain to enter all those dollar signs when I'm typing absolute cell
or range addresses into formulas. Using <ABS>, the <F4> key, makes it
much easier. Type the cell or range address into the formula, then stop.
Press <ABS> one or more times to cycle the address between relative, full
absolute, row absolute, and column absolute (you can view the changes on
the input line). Then finish entering the rest of the formula as you
would normally. <ABS> also works when you are editing a formula. Position
the cursor anywhere on a cell or range address and press <ABS> to cycle
through absolutes.

The @functions are one of Quattro Pro's standbys, but who can remember
all their names? When you're entering a formula that includes an
@function, try pressing <Alt>-<F3> to display an alphabetic list of all
available functions. Scroll through the list and select a function you
want, and it is entered in your formula automatically-including the
opening parenthesis after the function name.

No More Window Pains

When you're using multiple spreadsheet windows, you can move quickly to
any of the first nine windows by holding down <Alt> and pressing the
number of the window. Can't remember the window number? Press <Shift>-<F5
> for a list of window names you can select from. If you want to view all
windows at once, press <Ctrl>-T. You can click the desired window with
the mouse to make it active. Then, to zoom the active window to full
screen, press <Alt>-<F6>.

If you like seeing your windows on the screen in a particularly
convenient configuration, you can save time by saving the configuration
as a Workspace and recalling it later. Select /File-Workspace-Save, then
enter a name for the Workspace file. To restore a saved Workspace, start
Quattro Pro with the Workspace file name as a command-line argument (Q
MYCONFIG, for example) or select /File- Workspace-Restore once the
application is loaded. Remember that saving the Workspace does not save
the data in the windows; you must use /File-Save in each window to save
the spreadsheet data.

Beat the Oops! Blues

To keep your file intact, nothing beats a regular save (<Ctrl>-S or
/File-Save), of course. But what can you do to reverse individual errors
in your worksheet? Undo 'em. To enable the Undo feature, select
/Options-Other-Undo-Enable. If you make a mistake, press <Alt>-<F5> or
select /Edit-Undo to reverse it. Be aware that Undo takes some memory and
slows down some operations, so you may want to enable it only when you're
working on unfamiliar or complex tasks.

Working Smart in CorelDraw 3.0

Elect Select

Everybody knows CorelDraw is full of great tools for drawing and type
manipulation. But CorelDraw is also full of humbler but equally useful
shortcuts for selecting text.

For example, let's say you're using the Text tool to edit a page. To
select a word, double-click it; to select a sentence hold down <Ctrl> and
click it, to select a string of text click one end, hold down <Shift>,
and click the other end.

To move the insertion point within a text block, use the cursor keys;
press <Home> to move the insertion point to the beginning of the current
line and press <End> to move it to the end. <Ctrl>-<Home> takes it to the
beginning of a block; <Ctrl>-<End> moves it to the end of the block.
(Since it's sometimes hard to select text at the beginning of a block by
clicking and dragging over it, try clicking anywhere in the block,
pressing <Ctrl>-<Home>, then holding down the <Shift> key and clicking at
the place you want the selection to end.)

Face-Lifts

If Corel's default text font (24-point Avalon) isn't to your liking, you
can change it permanently by using the Windows Notepad to edit the
CORELDRW.INI file, located in your CorelDraw program directory. Find the
line that reads 'DefaultFont=Avalon, 1,24' in the [CDrawConfig] section,
and change 'Avalon' to the name of any PostScript font (provided you have
Adobe Type Manager or a PostScript printer) or TrueType font installed on
your system. The next setting, after the comma, lets you specify the
weight of the default font: 1 for normal, 2 for bold, 4 for italic, or 8
for bold italic. The final setting is the point size.

You can save time in a Corel session by setting the font for the current
insertion point. Just click on a blank part of the page with the Text
tool. Then choose the desired typeface and size in the Text roll-up (or
Character Attributes dialog box) and click Apply. When you type, the text
appearing at the insertion point will be the one you specified. But the
next time you click on a blank area of the page to make a new insertion
point, it will revert to the default.

To set a default face for an entire session, choose the Pick tool, making
sure no text block is selected, and define the desired attributes in the
dialog box; click OK to confirm and all new insertion points will be in
the face you chose. (The next time you run CorelDraw, it will revert to
the default face in the INI file.)

Path-Ology

Text attached to a path is linked to that path dynamically- you can
modify the text or the path separately without having to detach them from
each other. The trick: Hold down the <Ctrl> key and click on the text to
select it. You're now free to format or edit it as you would any text
block.

It's also easy to create and manipulate type. Let's say you're tightening
the spacing between the letters of some large display type to make it
easier to read. Try selecting the character and nudging it by pressing
the appropriate cursor key until it's in place. (In this case, I make
sure the Nudge value in the Preferences dialog box is set to only 1 or 2
points.) You can also move multiple characters by holding down the <Shift
> key while selecting them, or by dragging a selection marquee around
them.

Conversions and Reversions

There's a faster way to convert existing text from paragraph to artistic
mode, and vice versa. Instead of changing mode and retyping, choose the
Text tool, select the paragraph, and choose Edit*Copy. Then switch to the
Pick tool and choose Edit*Paste to create a new artistic text block. You
can go the other way by selecting a block of artistic text and choosing
Edit*Copy, then clicking and dragging with the Text tool to create a new
frame, and then choosing Edit*Paste. Remember: For this tip to work, you
have to use the Text tool to select the text.

Working Smart in Harvard Graphics 3.x

Default Is Mine

I never bother hunting around for charts and presentations. Instead, I
set up a default directory that tells the program exactly where my files
are. At the main menu, I select Setup-Program defaults and press <Enter>
three times to get to Directories Defaults (in the Program defaults
screen). Then I change any of the default directories-for Data, Import,
and Work files, for example-to the directories where I keep those types
of files.

Do the Keyboard Shuffle

Whenever you finish a task using the keyboard, such as typing text in a
form, press <F10> to get to the next menu, or press <Esc> to return to
the previous screen. If you're using a mouse and you've finished a task,
just press the right button to continue.

And if you forget Harvard's litany of keystroke shortcuts while working
on a chart-such as <Ctrl>-N to edit notes, <Ctrl>-B to insert fractions
and other special characters, and <Ctrl>-P to print a chart-there's an
easier way to remember them. Just press <Ctrl>-<F1> to produce a pop-up
list of keyboard shortcuts.

Stop Mousing Around

When I'm using the Draw feature, it's often faster to use keyboard
shortcuts than to mouse around. To select an editing tool, type the first
letter of the tool's name-say, C for Copy, P for Paste, G for Group, or U
for Ungroup-and then press <Enter>. For tools that start with the same
letter-such as Delete, Duplicate, and Disconnect-I press the letter
repeatedly until the tool I want is highlighted, and then press <Enter>.

You can also use the <Ctrl> key in combination with letter keys to bypass
pulldown menus or select another drawing tool. For example, <Ctrl>-G gets
you a chart, <Ctrl>-S saves a chart, and <Ctrl>-U gives you Undo. Press
<Ctrl>-T to toggle between the Text tool and the Select tool.

It's a Draw

I hate having to wait for Harvard to redraw an entire chart every time I
make a change. For top-speed redraw, press <F8>1 to access the Redraw
options list, set the redrawing quality to draft, and select No for all
of the other display options (they control gradients, bit maps,
subcharts, and button names). You can cancel a Redraw in progress by
hitting <Esc> and restart the redraw by pressing <Ctrl>-D.

Zippy Printing

To improve printing speed for draft copies, try the following tips.

1. From the main menu, select Setup-Printer 1 (assuming Printer 1 is your
draft printer) to open the Printer 1 Setup menu. Select Yes for Use
Spooler (which gets you back to work in Harvard faster) and Draft for
Quality.

2. When working on a chart, press <Ctrl>-P (to print) and <F8> to open
the Printer Options menu. Select No for Draw background color. If your
printer comes with built-in fonts, select Yes for the Use Hardware Fonts
Only option.

Working Smart in PageMaker

A Zoom With a View

I find that PageMaker does my bidding most successfully if I treat
keyboard and mouse as equal partners. At first, it was a little like
learning to drive with a stick shift, but with a little effort, <Shift
>-clicking, <Ctrl>-dragging, and other combined operations became second
nature.

For example, to toggle between actual view (100 percent) and
fit-in-window sizes, I just click on the right mouse button. To zoom into
200 percent magnification, I hold down <Shift> while right-clicking the
mouse. To zoom out to see two facing pages and the entire pasteboard, I
hold down <Shift> while choosing Page-Fit in window or just press <Shift
>- <Ctrl>-W.

Page Pranks

Tired of the scroll bars? Don't use them. Instead, hold down <Alt> and
drag to access the grabber-hand pointer, which lets you move the page in
any direction. And don't bother messing with the page icons when you want
to turn a page. Instead, press <F12> to move forward a page and <F11> to
move back one. To go to a specific page, press <Ctrl>-G, enter the page
number, and press <Enter>.

Story Time

Mice are great for selecting text, but you can also use the text tool and
double-click on a word to select it, or triple-click to select a
paragraph. Press <Ctrl>-A to select all the text in the current story.

If you prefer to keep your hands on the keyboard, hold down <Shift>-<Ctrl
> and press <Right> or <Left> to select the next or previous word.
Pressing <Shift>-<Ctrl> with <Up> or <Down> selects entire paragraphs.

To check spelling or to search and replace characters, triple-click a
text block with the Arrow tool or press <Ctrl>-E to enter the Story
Editor, then choose Edit- Spelling or press <Ctrl>-L. If your insertion
point is blinking inside the story already, press <Ctrl>-E. Press <Ctrl
>-E again to return to the layout view.

Editing With Style

Style sheets are real work-savers. Any time you format a paragraph of
text, save it to a style sheet so you can reapply the formatting to other
paragraphs easily. Assuming the Style palette is available (<Ctrl>-Y),
just hold down <Ctrl> while clicking on the No style option to define a
new style. If you ever want to edit the style sheet-and consequently
reformat all text associated with that style- <Ctrl>-click on its name in
the Style palette.

Grappling With Graphics

There's no substitute for the mouse when selecting graphics. But when one
graphic overlaps another, or when text and graphics overlap, the mouse
isn't enough. Instead, press <Ctrl>-click to select the top object (text
block or graphic) in a stack, <Ctrl>-right click again to select the next
one down, and so on until you select the object you want. When you drag
that object, it automatically moves to the front of the stack.

If you use photographic scans and other bit-mapped images (PCX or TIFF
files), remember this trick: To ensure that the resolution of your
imported image matches the resolution of your final output device-so you
don't get any unsightly patterns showing up in your pictures-select the
printer model using the File*Target printer command, then hold down
<Shift>-<Ctrl> and drag a corner handle of the image to scale it.

Tooling Around

Here's a tip that will elevate you from PageMaker novice to all-around
pro. Close the Toolbox-it consumes too much valuable space on screen-and
assign the following keyboard equivalents to the inner recesses of your
personal memory banks.

To select the Text tool, press <Shift>-<F4>. To toggle back to the Arrow
tool, press <F9>. You can access the other tools from the keyboard as
well-<Shift>-<F2> selects the Line tool, <Shift>-<F8> gets the Crop
tool-but how often do you use them? For most situations, <Shift>-<F4> and
<F9> are all you need.

Working Smart in dBASE IV

Strings Attached

With dBASE, I get an eclectic menu of working environments- the Control
Center, the infamous dot prompt, a group of interactive form designers,
and a built-in programming language. One key to working smarter with
dBASE is to take advantage of what each mode has to offer.

Because dBASE has a built-in programming language, it offers a wide array
of functions that let me carry out specialized calculations and data
transformations. (Even if you're allergic to programming, you can use
these functions to manipulate dates and character strings.)

For example, I sometimes use the UPPER() function to convert a string to
all uppercase. To print a name field in uppercase on a report, I add the
expression UPPER(Name) to the report, and to index on the state,
regardless of how the state abbreviation was entered, I use the
expression UPPER(State) in the index key expression.

The TRIM () function removes trailing blank spaces from a string. You can
use this function to combine strings on reports and labels and avoid
unsightly gaps that would result from partly empty fields, as in the
expression TRIM(City) + ", " + State + " " + ZIP. For example, you can
use an array of date manipulation functions to format dates on reports,
including CDOW(duedate), which evaluates to the day of the week, spelled
out (for example, 'Tuesday') and CMONTH(duedate), which yields the name
of the month.

Index Fingers

dBASE can index on a field of any data type, but when you combine fields
of different data types, you can use functions to convert all of them to
character strings. For example, to index a transaction file on a
character field called IDCODE, and within each IDCODE group, by a date
field called TRANDATE, you can use the DTOS function (which converts a
date to a character string in year/month/day order to achieve correct
chronological order) in an expression like Idcode + DTOS(Trandate). To
index in reverse chronological order, you need a more complicated
expression that subtracts the date from an arbitrary future date later
than any you anticipate in your database (say, December 31, 1999). The
subtraction yields the number of days between the two dates, and this
number will be smaller for later dates; those which will fall earlier in
indexed order. To combine this numeric result with a character field, you
can use the STR function to convert it to a four-digit number, as
follows: Idcode + STR({12/31/99} - Trandate, 4).

Go Dotty

If you are new to dBASE and have been working exclusively in the menu
system, you can work a lot faster with the dot prompt commands than you
can using the menu-driven Query by Example (QBE). For example, to compute
more than one summary statistic based on the same field, you must add two
copies of the database to the query. Using the CALCULATE command at the
dot prompt, you can carry out multiple calculations easily. The formula
CALCULATE MIN(Trandate), MAX(Trandate), SUM(Amount), AVG(Amount),
MAX(Amount) calculates the earliest and latest transaction dates and the
sum, average, and maximum transaction amounts.

Instead of using QBE exclusively to carry out inquiries based on multiple
databases, you can open and link the files at the dot prompt using the
USE, SET RELATION TO, and SET SKIP TO commands. These let you link
databases based on any expression, not just a field or index present in
both files. For example, you could link a name and address database to a
transaction file that's indexed, like the expression described above, on
a character field and a date. To accomplish this from the dot prompt,
open both databases, each in its own numbered work area and with the
transaction field ordered on the combined character and date index (in
this example, called IdDate):

SELECT 1

USE Names ORDER StateId

SELECT 2

USE Trans ORDER IdDate

To establish the link, use a SET RELATION command executed from the work
area you want to be active, followed by a SET SKIP command if the
relationship is one-to-many:

SELECT 1

SET RELATION TO Idcode INTO Trans

SET SKIP TO Trans

After some experience working at the dot prompt, you'll be surprised at
the power, speed, and flexibility you'll gain.

-Miriam Liskin

Working Smart in Paradox 4.0 for DOS

Field Flux

I love Paradox's report designer but there's no easy way to copy and move
fields. Here are a few quick tricks to increase efficiency.

To copy a calculated field, use the Instant Scripts feature. First I
position the cursor where I want the field and press <Alt>-<F3> to start
recording. Next, I use Field*Place* Calculated to create the calculated
field. When the field is in place, I press <Alt>-<F3> again to stop
recording the script. Then I move the cursor to the next place I want to
use the same field (or a similar one) and press <Alt>-<F4> to run the
script and create a new field. If I need to change the expression, I use
Field-Reformat.

If you need to move a field at the left margin to the end of the previous
line in a free-form report, press <Insert> to go into Insert mode, place
the cursor at the beginning of the line and press <Backspace>. And in
tabular reports, save time by pressing <Ctrl>-R to rotate a column just
like when you are viewing a table and pressing <Tab> or <Shift>- <Tab> to
move the cursor from column to column.

A New Image

Sometimes you'd like to see a different form than the default F form that
Paradox uses when you press <F7>, or use the Form Speedbar button. To
change the default, use Image- PickForm to show the form you want to use,
and then Image- KeepSet.

There's no rule that says you have to keep the standard R report in its
original form. If you want to print a different report when you press
<Alt>-<F7>, you can copy the report of your choice to the R slot using
Tools-Copy-Report- SameTable.

Edit, CoEdit

Paradox's hot-keys in Edit and CoEdit mode make it easy to edit tables
fast. <Ctrl>-<Backspace> erases an entire field; <Ctrl>-D copies a field
value from the previous record into an empty field, and <Ctrl>-F, <Alt>-
<F5>, or a double-click of the mouse button, brings you into Field View,
where you can readily change a field value without having to erase it
first.

If you make a mistake, you can use Undo (<Ctrl>-U) to reinsert a deleted
record, delete an inserted record, or return an edited record to its
original state. <F9> brings you into Edit mode when a table is in your
work space; similarly, <Alt>-<F9> or the CoEdit button on the Speedbar
puts you into CoEdit. You can move freely between table windows while
editing or coediting by pressing <F3>, <F4>, or <Ctrl>-<F4>.

ValCheck It Out

When it comes to data entry, the ValCheck feature is an ideal time-saver.
You can use it to do things like fill in and format values and check
against lookup tables. To add ValChecks to a table while you're editing,
choose ValCheck*Define while in Edit mode.

Spacebar, the Final Frontier

Why waste time typing in dates in the Date field? Instead, when you're in
the default mm/dd/yy format, just press <Space> to fill in the current
month, tap again for the current day, and tap a third time to fill in the
year.

Sort It Out

If you've been relying on the Sort command to order records for a report,
you have to use it every time you run your report. It's much easier to
use the Group command in Report mode. Groupings always override the
sorted order of the underlying report table, and you have to add them to
your report design only once.

Working Smart in Quicken 6.0

Quick Starts

I like Quicken because among other things, it lets me work fast. I can
load files automatically, change between accounts, and use some easy
keyboard shortcuts to get my accounting over and done with.

For example, let's say I know the account I'm going to use- call it
'Cash92'-I just type Q Cash92 at the DOS prompt, and Quicken loads it
automatically. If I have more than one file, I type the account name
followed by a space and the file name. For example, Q Wells Business gets
me into my Business file and Wells account.

Jump Shots

Quicken's shortcut keys let you jump from one place to another with
amazing agility. For example, you can assign a Quick Key number to each
of nine accounts and change accounts fast by holding down <Ctrl> and
pressing the corresponding number. It's easy to copy a transaction within
the same account or to another account in the same file: Press <Ctrl>-
<Insert> on the transaction you want to copy and paste it into an empty
transaction with <Ctrl>-<Insert>.

Fiddling with the register's date field when entering data that's very
old gets, well, kind of old. Try T for today, and M for the beginning of
the month. It's even better to use Quicken's Quick Calendar: Press <Ctrl
>-K to pop it up, scroll to the date you want, and press <F9> to paste it
in.

Why plow through a half-dozen keystrokes to create the same report each
session? Once the report's on screen, memorize it with <Ctrl>-M. Forgot
to memorize it? Use <Ctrl>-Z to call up the last report you used.

Say you're in a cash flow report and want to figure out how $10,000 got
into the Miscellaneous category, before your boss does. With your cursor
on a particular figure, press <Ctrl>-Z to display the list of the
transactions that produce the total amount.

Want to recategorize an item? Press <F9> to get back to the Register,
<Ctrl>-T to get to the list, and <Ctrl>-E to change the category. <Ctrl
>-Z zaps you back to the report.

Bill Time

Do you pay the same bills at the same time every month? There's no need
to remember the date or the categories these bills fall into. Quicken
will batch your memorized transactions, remind you when they're due , and
enter the entire group into your register. All you have to do is enter
the amount of each bill and print them. From the Register, press <Ctrl>-J
and just fill in the blanks.

Filling It Up

You probably take advantage of QuickFill-Quicken's database of every
check you write-to fill in transaction fields automatically. But creating
memorized transactions for regular events can be done even more quickly.
Because I do most of my banking through convenient automated teller
machines, I've created some memorized transactions for the typical
amounts I withdraw. For example, when I press 1 from the Payee field,
QuickFill brings up '100ATM' and 6 gets '60ATM,' each with the correct
amount of the transaction already filled in.

Transfer Tricks

It's easy to transfer between accounts in Quicken. Say you are thinking
of selling your house, so you keep careful track of all home improvement
expenditures and add them to the base cost of your house.

The easiest way to go about doing this is to set up a new account, let's
say, Home Improve, choose Other Asset for the type of account, and enter
the price you paid for your house. The next time you pay for something
that's considered a legitimate home improvement, choose your Home Improve
account and you'll automatically tally the improvement into the increased
value of your house.

-Steve Bass

