Title:     Team 1-2-3 with your word processor for effective reports;
           here's how you can easily import data into your WordPerfect,
           Word, or Ami Pro document.
             (includes related articles on linking techniques and
             formatting spreadsheet data in reports) (Lotus: Getting the
             Most from 1-2-3 & Other Lotus Software)
Author:    Kenny, Catherine


Abstract:  Techniques are described for importing spreadsheet data into
           word processing documents for inclusion in reports. After
           linking a 1-2-3 worksheet with a word processor, the data need
           not be reentered, but while the numeric format of the 1-2-3
           data is imported as well, WYSIWYG formatting may not make the
           transition. Character formatting applied to the 1-2-3 data in
           a word processor is wiped out every time the spreadsheet data
           is updated, but many word processors let users define styles
           and apply them to data, which makes it easy to reapply formats
           after the report is updated. The two ways to bring data into a
           word processor are by importing it and by linking it:
           importing data essentially copies it into the word processing
           document, while linking it allows the linked data to remain
           connected to the worksheet rather than becoming part of the
           document. Which technique to use for specific situations and
           the linking and importing features of popular word processing
           programs are described.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Full Text:

In 1-2-3 you can do a lot of things well, but you can't do everything.
When you need to merge your 1-2-3 worksheet data into a company report,
memo, or newsletter, you're better off creating the document in a word
processor and then bringing in the spreadsheet data.

1-2-3 lacks the word processing power to create anything more complex
than a simple one-page report. For example, 1- 2-3 lacks a spelling
checker, doesn't let you set important formats such as line spacing and
paragraph indentations, and can't handle more than one page of text.
Almost any word processing program, on the other hand, lets you
manipulate text and numbers in virtually any way imaginable. Bringing
your spreadsheet data into your word processor lets you apply all that
power so you can create professional-looking reports with the numbers
generated in 1-2-3.

Sophisticated links mean that once you link a 1-2-3 worksheet with your
word processor, you never have to reenter the data. Suppose you linked
the data in a large budget worksheet to a monthly report. As you change
the worksheet's numbers, the numbers in the report change automatically.

Be forewarned, however, that while the numeric format of your 1-2-3 data
travels with it, Wysiwyg formatting may be left behind. And any character
formatting you apply to the 1-2-3 data in your word processor gets wiped
out each time you update the spreadsheet data. On the other hand, many
word processors let you define styles and apply those to the data, making
it easy to reapply the formats after the report has been updated.

Combining worksheet data with a word processing document is easy because
1-2-3 is a de facto standard, which means that most word processors make
special provisions for 1-2-3 data. To demonstrate just how easy it is,
we'll show you how to combine 1-2-3 data with documents created in
WordPerfect 5.1 for DOS and Windows, Microsoft Word 5.5 for DOS,
Microsoft Word for Windows 2.0, and Ami Pro 3.0.

There are two ways to bring worksheet data into your word processor:
importing and linking. When you import data, you are essentially copying
it into the word processing document. The data becomes part of the
document. If you later change the data in the worksheet, those changes
will not be reflected in the document.

Linked data remains connected to the worksheet rather than becoming part
of the document. When you link worksheet data to a word processing
document, you can view a -copy' of the 1-2-3 data through the document.
If you change the linked data in the worksheet, the data in the document
will reflect those changes. But if you change the data in your word
processor, it will be replaced by the worksheet data the next time the
worksheet is updated. If you delete the worksheet, the document will no
longer contain the linked data.

Which method should you use to combine data with a report? That depends
on the type of data in your worksheet. If the data is relatively static,
you're better off importing it. For example, if you're creating a report
that uses the sales figures from the past two years, you should import
those figures since they won't change. Linking makes more sense when
you're working with data that's likely to change. Reports highlighting
cumulative sales figures, for example, should contain linked data.

DOS word processors can read data from both DOS and Windows spreadsheets,
although the methods differ slightly. When you import worksheet data into
a DOS word processor, it arrives as delimited ASCII text, stripped of
attributes and separated by tab stops.

WordPerfect 5.1 for DOS. The top-selling DOS word processor accepts 1-2-3
data without a hitch. WordPerfect recognizes the individual sheets in a
multisheet file, and it lets you import specific named ranges. You can
import data as delimited text or as a table with the same column and row
format as the source worksheet. Either way, only minimal reformatting is
needed to create a usable document.

To import 1-2-3 worksheet data into a WordPerfect document, position the
cursor and select File-Text In-Spreadsheet- Import. Select Filename from
the Spreadsheet Import screen, and enter the path name of the file.
Select Range and indicate the range you want to import. Choose Type and
indicate Table or Text. Finally, select Perform Import. Figure 1 shows
worksheet data imported into WordPerfect as a table.

Links between 1-2-3 data and WordPerfect documents are also easy to
create and maintain. To create a link, select File- Text
In-Spreadsheet-Create Link. Select Filename from the Spreadsheet Import
screen, and enter the path name of the file that contains the data you
want to link. Select Range and indicate the range you want to link.
Select Type and choose Table or Text, then select Perform Link.
WordPerfect inserts codes at the beginning and end of the linked data
identifying the source file and range. To update the linked data, choose
File-Text In-Spreadsheet-Link Options- Update All Links. WordPerfect
replaces the data between the codes with updated data.

If you want the linked data to be updated every time you retrieve the
WordPerfect document, select File-Text In- Spreadsheet-Link Options and
set the Update on Retrieve option to Yes.

Microsoft Word 5.5. Microsoft Word offers most of WordPerfect's importing
and linking capabilities, with a few important exceptions. Word can't
import or link spreadsheet data as a table, and it doesn't automatically
update linked data.

To import 1-2-3 data into a Word document, select Insert- File. In the
resulting dialog box's File text box, enter the name of the file that
contains the data you want to import. Click the arrow in the Range text
box and indicate the range you want to import: Select All to import the
entire worksheet, indicate the sheet letter to import the entire active
sheet of a multisheet file, select an assigned range name, or type the
range address. Click OK. Word imports the data with tabs defined by the
document's current style sheet. You'll have to modify the current tab
settings to make the data presentable.

To link 1-2-3 data to a Word document, select Insert-File, use the File
and Range text boxes to enter the name of the file and range you want to
link, select Link, then click OK. Word inserts the data separated by tabs
and surrounds it with codes that mark the beginning and end of the data,
as shown in Figure 2. If these codes are not visible, select View-Layout,
View-Preferences, and Show Hidden.

To update the linked data, place the cell pointer in the area of the
document that contains the linked data, select Insert-File, and click
Update Link. Word updates all the data between the codes. You can update
multiple links in the same document by pressing <Ctrl>-5 to highlight the
entire document and selecting Insert-File-Update Link. Word stops at each
link and asks you to verify the update.

Despite all you may have heard about how hard mixing DOS and Windows
programs is, it's relatively easy to transport data between the two
environments. WordPerfect 5.1 for Windows, Microsoft Word for Windows
2.0, and Ami Pro 3.0 all provide commands that import data from DOS
releases of 1-2-3. WordPerfect for Windows and WinWord also let you link
spreadsheet data.

WordPerfect 5.1 for Windows. To import 1-2-3 for DOS data into
WordPerfect for Windows, select Tools-Spreadsheet- Import. In the Import
Spreadsheet dialog box, enter the name of the worksheet file in the
Filename box, enter the range in the Range text box, use the Range Name
list box to select the entire spreadsheet or a named range, indicate
Table or Text, and click OK.

To link the data, select Tools-Spreadsheet-Create Link and indicate the
file name and range in the resulting dialog box, as above. To update the
linked data, select Tools- Spreadsheet-Update All Links. Figure 3 shows a
link between WordPerfect for Windows and 1-2-3 for DOS data.

Microsoft Word for Windows 2.0. Spreadsheet data is easier to manipulate
and format in WinWord than in Word for DOS because it's transferred as a
table, as shown in Figure 4. To import 1-2-3 for DOS data into a WinWord
document, select Insert-File, select All Files in the List Files of Type
box, use the Drives and Directories buttons to specify the file, enter
the range address in the Range text box, and click OK. If 1-2-3 is not
already selected in the Convert File dialog box, select it from the list
and click OK.

To link 1-2-3 for DOS data to a WinWord document, select Insert-File and
enter the information as above, select Link to File, and click OK. Again,
if 1-2-3 is not selected in the Convert File dialog box, select it from
the list and click OK.

To update linked data, place the cursor anywhere in the table, select
Edit-Links, and click Update Now. To link a different range, select
Edit-Links, click Change Link, and enter the appropriate information.

Ami Pro 3.0. To import 1-2-3 for DOS data into an Ami Pro document, place
the cursor where you want to insert the data and choose File-Open. In the
File Open dialog box, click the arrow in the List Files of Type box;
select 1-2-3 if you're using release 2.x, or 1-2-3 rel 3 if you're using
3.x. Enter the path name of the file or click the appropriate drive and
directory buttons, select the file name from the Files box, and click
Insert. Indicate the import options you want in the Import dialog box. To
import a range of data, select Range and enter the range address or a
defined range name in the text box. To import the data into an Ami Pro
table, select Create Table. Figure 5 shows a range of 1-2-3 for DOS data
in an Ami Pro document.

The Windows Clipboard and Dynamic Data Exchange (DDE) make it easy to
transfer data between programs. In a process similar to importing in DOS,
you can copy data from any Windows program onto the Clipboard, then paste
it into any other Windows program. DDE offers a convenient way to
establish a link between any two Windows programs.

You can use a word processor's internal File-Import commands to import
data from your worksheet, but you'll find that using the Clipboard is
much easier. You don't have to memorize the name of the file or the range
of cells you want to import. You just open both files, select the 1-2-3/W
range you want, and copy the data to the Clipboard using the Edit-Copy
command. Then switch to the word processor and paste the data into your
document by selecting Edit-Paste.

Linking is slightly more complicated. DDE establishes an active link
between two programs, which means that as long as both applications are
open at the same time, the data in the client application-the application
receiving the data-is automatically updated when you change it in the
server application. When you use the File- Import methods, you must
update the data manually.

To create a DDE link, both programs must be open and both files must be
named. If you can't access the Link commands in your word processor, take
a moment to make sure both files have a name. To steer around memory
problems that may be caused by two open Windows applications, use active
links only when necessary. Often you can shut down the server application
once the link has been established. When you want to refresh the link in
the client application, restart the server application and manually
update the link.

WordPerfect 5.1 for Windows. This program's importing and linking
commands are very similar to those in the DOS version. But the program
has trouble transferring formats, as illustrated in Figure 6. Your best
bet is to create named styles and reapply the formatting after every
update.

To establish a DDE link between your 1-2-3/W data and a WordPerfect
document, highlight the data in 1-2-3/W, select Edit-Copy, then switch to
WordPerfect. Place the cursor where the data should appear, and select
Edit-Link-Paste Link.

To change any of the link information, select Edit-Link- Edit.
WordPerfect displays the names of all the active links in the document in
the Edit DDE Link dialog box. Select the name of the link from this list,
and enter a new name for it in the New Link Name text box. Then change
the source file or data range in the Source File and Item box. The
current link information is displayed in the box in the lower right
corner of the screen. Click OK when you have finished.

Microsoft Word for Windows 2.0. This best-selling word processor does a
better job of handling spreadsheet data than WordPerfect for Windows. You
can import data from both the DOS and Windows versions of 1-2-3, and
WinWord preserves 1-2-3's numeric formatting. However, WinWord imports
only limited text formatting, and updating the source data wipes out any
formatting added in WinWord.

To get around this problem, either refrain from making formatting changes
until you're sure the 1-2-3 data won't change (which kind of defeats the
purpose of linking), or import the data as a linked graphic image.
Importing 1-2-3/W data as a graphic means you can't edit it in the word
processor, but at least this approach retains the formatting when you
change the data in 1-2-3/W. Figure 7 shows 1-2-3/W data imported as a
graphic image.

In 1-2-3/W, highlight the range you want to link, and select Edit-Copy.
Switch to WinWord, position the cursor where you want the data to appear,
and select Edit- Paste Special. The Paste Special dialog box shows the
type of data currently in the Clipboard and the formats in which the data
is available. To paste the data as a graphic, select Picture and click
Paste Link. If codes appear in your document instead of the graphic
image, select View-Field Codes to turn off the display.

Ami Pro 3.0. Despite Lotus Development Corporation's Working Together
strategy, linking 1-2-3/W data to Ami Pro leaves a lot to be desired. Ami
Pro has trouble reading numeric formats from 1-2-3/W. And although Ami
Pro imports worksheet data in a table format and transfers attributes
such as fonts, colors, and borders, the process can scramble internal
formatting. For example, in Ami Pro, values that are formatted as labels
are interpreted as values, while values with numeric formatting, such as
Currency, show up as labels. You'll need to manually adjust the data in
Ami Pro every time the data in 1-2-3/W is updated.

As in WinWord, every update wipes out formatting. The best approach here
is also to import the data as a graphic image. After you format the
1-2-3/W data, highlight the range and choose Edit-Copy. Then switch to
Ami Pro, position the cursor where you want the data to appear, select
Edit-Paste Special, indicate Windows Metafile, and click OK. Ami Pro
places a graphic image of the worksheet in the document, as shown in
Figure 8.

Linking 1-2-3 worksheet data with word processing files is relatively
easy, but it isn't foolproof. Still, with a little practice, you'll find
that it can help you to quickly create high-quality documents without
introducing any typing errors. Catherine Kenny is an assistant editor for
PC World Lotus Edition.

1. Assign a name to the range you want to link. If you add or delete
columns and rows within a named range, the data in your word processor
will be updated automatically.

2. Apply numeric formats before you import data, text formats after. In
most cases, 1-2-3's currency signs, commas, and decimal places travel
with the data. Wysiwyg formats don't, so don't waste time dressing up
your data in the spreadsheet. Use the formatting and style commands in
your word processor instead.

3. Keep linking information current. If you rename the worksheet file or
move it to another directory, you must update the linking information in
your word processor. Also, if you share your files on a network, make
sure other users know when a worksheet file is linked.

Now that you've managed to get your 1-2-3 data into your word processor,
you need to decide how you want it to look. You may be tempted to go wild
with all the new formatting options, but that could defeat your purpose.
If you apply too much formatting to your document, nothing will stand
out. The following design tips will help keep your spreadsheet data in
sync with your word processing document.

1. Add lots of space around numbers. Cramped tables are hard to read. To
set the worksheet data apart from the rest of the document, set at least
a half-inch indent or margin between the edge of the table and the text.
Also, add a line or two of space at the top and bottom of the table. If
you increase the spacing between columns and rows, make sure it's
consistent.

2. Use a typeface that works well with tabular data, such as Times Roman.
A serif font tends to produce characters that are easier to read, and
columns of data will align more evenly. If you're working with a large
block of data, however, you may find that a sans serif font such as
Helvetica has crisper-looking numbers.

3. Set the spreadsheet data a point or two smaller than the rest of the
text. Type that's between 8 and 11 points works well.

4. Separate table elements with rules. For example, a rule between the
column headings and the data emphasizes the column headings. Separating
the Total row from the data with a rule draws attention to the bottom
line. If space is tight, separate elements with lines and shading, using
the lightest shade possible and setting the underlying text in bold.

5. Use text attributes to emphasize different passages of spreadsheet
data. For example, set row headings in italics and set column headings in
boldface to help orient the reader. Just don't overdo it.
