Title:     Microsoft Word.
             (includes related article on customizing Microsoft Word for
             Windows's startup) (201 Hot Windows Secrets)


Abstract:  Tips on how to better use Microsoft Corp's Word for Windows
           word processing package are offered. The tips range from how
           to expedite copy formatting to tuning the zoom controls. Word
           users can align document text such as letterheads, headers and
           footers. Users can copy character formatting quickly by
           highlighting the text needed to be changed, holding down the
           control-shift key, and then clicking the left mouse button on
           any area of text with the formatting that needs to be copied.
           Additional tips on Word for Windows are discussed.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Full Text:

Text Alignment as You Like It

Letterheads, headers, and footers often call for left-aligned,
right-aligned, and centered text on the same line. Word's regular text
formatting can't manage this, but the Table feature can. To mix all three
alignments on a line, place the insertion point where you want the line
to appear, and choose Table, Insert Table. Specify three columns and one
row for your table, and click on OK. Select the entire table, choose
Format, Paragraph, and make sure that Indentation is set to zero on the
left and the right. Then type text in each of the cells, and use the
paragraph-justification buttons on your toolbar to select left
justification for the leftmost cell, centered justification for the
middle one, and right justification on the right.

Copy Formatting Fast

To copy character formatting quickly, highlight the text you want to
change, hold down Ctrl-Shift, and click with the left mouse button on any
area of text with the formatting you want to copy. Copy paragraph
formatting the same way, but click in the selection bar to the left of
the paragraph whose formatting you want to copy. Note: This feature may
work erratically with Word 2.0 releases prior to August 31, 1992.

Banish White Space with Text Wrap

Use a frame to make text flow around a graphical object such as an
inserted chart or a PCX file. First, position the cursor on a blank line
(a line containing only a carriage return), and select Insert, Picture.
Select the graphics file you want to insert and click on OK. The picture
appears on a line by itself.

Select the image by clicking on its center. Select Insert, Frame to put a
frame around the graphic. (If you're not already in Page Layout view,
answer Yes when Word asks you if you want to switch.) If there's room
between the margins, the text wraps around a frame, select the frame and
choose Format, Frame, Text Wrapping: None to place the graphic on its own
line.

Run Macros Faster from Buttons

To create a button in your document that will run any Word macro, choose
Insert, Field, and select Macro Button. Type the name of a macro
immediately following the term macrobutton in the Field Code: box, then
type the text identifying the button. Click on OK to return to your
document. To edit the macro button, ensure that field codes are turned on
(choose View, Field Codes). To run the macro, turn off the field codes
display so that only the button text is visible, and double-click on this
text. You can also insert Microsoft Draw objects or other graphical
objects in place of the button text.

Make Word Fill the Screen

There's an easy way to eliminate Word's annoying tendency to open with a
different window size every time it starts up. Create a macro that
maximizes Word, and call it AUTOEXEC to have Word run the macro whenever
it starts. Select Tools, Macro, and type AUTOEXEC in the Macro Name: box.
Then click on Edit. Type in the following line between the lines Sub Main
and End Sub:

If AppMaximize() = 0 Then AppMaximize

Save your changes and exit. When you restart WinWord, this macro checks
to see if Word's application window is maximized. If it's not, the macro
maximizes it for you. You can also put any other commands in the AUTOEXEC
macro that you want to run whenever you start Word.

KILLER TIP

CUSTOMIZE WORD STARTUP

Make Word open the last document you worked on as soon as it starts.
Select the Word icon in Program Manager, press Alt-Enter, then place the
cursor at the end of the text in the Command Line: box. Add a space, then
type/MFile1 at the end of this line.

Or, to start a new document based on the automated letter template
LETBLOCK, create the following macro, named NEWLETTER.

Sub Main

FileNew .NewTemplate = 0, .Template = "LETBLOCK"

End Sub

Then use the command line C: [unkeyable]WORD20[unkeyable]WINWORD.EXE
/MNewLetter to start WinWord and begin a new letter. You may want to
create several macros--one for each of your document templates--and then
create a separate Program Manager icon that runs each. In Program
Manager, choose File, New, and select Program Item. Then specify the Word
command line, complete with a /M switch and macro name, and give the icon
a title that identifies the template with which it opens. Note: Word
won't run the AUTOEXEC macro when you specify a macro on the command
line.

Get Rid of Document1

To start Word without the usual blank document, select the Word icon in
Program Manager and press Alt-Enter to bring up the Program Item
Properties dialog box. The Command Line: box contains the path and
filename of WinWord. Add a /N (slash N) to the end of this command line.
The line should now look something like this:

C: [unkeyable]WORD20[unkeyable]WINWORD.EXE /N

Click on OK. When you start WinWord, you'll get a blank screen.

Fine-Tune Your Zoom Controls

To move quickly between views, use the ViewZoom command on your toolbar.
Select Tools, Options, and select the Toolbar set of options. Select a
button you don't use from the Tool to Change: box. Pick a new button face
(such as the binoculars icon), then select Commands in the Show: box.
Scroll through the list of commands and select ViewZoom, then click on
OK.

When you click on the ViewZoom button, a large arrow drops down from the
button. Hold down the mouse button, and scroll up and down this arrow to
set the degree of magnification you want. When you release the mouse
button, your document is zoomed to that degree.
