Title:     Windows imports key to this Mac offering.
             (Microsoft Corp.'s Word for Macintosh 5.1 word processing
             software)
Author:    Blackwell, Gerry


Abstract:  Microsoft Corp's Word for the Macintosh 5.1 word processing
           software imports new features from the Windows version. Among
           these features are the embedded object concept that allows
           inserting charts and graphs, tool bars, a button that makes
           using the program easier, and the Create Envelope function for
           generating a ready-to-print envelope file. When using Create
           Envelope, Mac Word 5.1 is able to provide the ability for
           storing and retrieving often-used addresses, a feature that is
           not available in the Windows version. Another new feature that
           is pure Mac is the text annotation facility that allows the
           insert of an annotation anywhere in the document. With Mac
           Word 5.1 too, a user can 'drop cap' letters, words or portions
           of text with just a few keystrokes. A minor flaw is that when
           the annotation box is open on the screen, the user cannot work
           on the main document.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Full Text:

 Here's a switch: Macintosh aping Windows. The new version of Microsoft
Word for Macintosh, 5.1, includes a bunch of nifty new features, of which
the most visible are imports from the Windows version of the product.

 Expect to see more 'cultural' borrowings of this kind as Mac-Windows
cross-platform applications begin to proliferate. Witness the recent dual
introduction of Claris FileMaker Pro for Mac and Windows.

 The button bar introduced with Mac Word 5.1 is a major ease-of-use
enhancement. As with the WinWord implementation, it comes already
configured with default buttons for commonly-used functions - 15 or 26 in
the Mac environment, depending on your screen size. But you can easily
customize the bar, replacing default buttons with others to activate any
command available.

 Unlike the Windows version you can have the button bar show up
horizontally just below the menu bar, the default position, or vertically
on the edge of the document window, left or right. Of course, if you put
it along the side, you can't display as many buttons. Mac Word 5.1 also
includes a bigger library of button icons than WinWord for use when
customizing the bar.

 Microsoft has borrowed the Windows embedded object concept again to
provide a facility for inserting graphs and charts created with a
Windows-like applet shipped with the product.

 It joins the drawing tool, added in an earlier version. A button for the
graphing tool appears along with drawing and table-making tool buttons on
the ribbon in the document window. In the Windows version, these buttons
all take up valuable real estate on the button bar.

 The current mania for button and tool bars in Windows applications seems
a logical extension to the interface Windows originally borrowed from the
Mac. So it's surprising this feature is only now being added to Mac Word.

 The Create Envelop feature is another useful little work saver brought
over from WinWord. By highlighting an address in a Word document, then
selecting the Create Envelop command from the Tools menu (or clicking on
the button on the button bar), you can quickly generate a ready-to-print
envelope file without going to the bother of setting up the printer and
keying in the addresses.

 Again, Mac Word goes one better than WinWord. It provides a facility for
storing often-used addresses and retrieving them when using Create
Envelopes.

 The other major new features in 5.1 are pure Mac - so far. The text
annotation facility could be a real boon for companies that pass Word
files around a lot on disk or on a network. You can insert an annotation
anywhere in the document by selecting Annotation from the Insert menu.
Key in a note in the dialogue box that pops up, mark it with your
initials and click to insert the annotation.

 A graphic, not the annotation itself, appears in the document. The
graphic is unfortunately too big to fit in a regular line space, though,
so it tends to break up the text. Double click on the graphic and the
annotation box opens up revealing the text.

 One small flaw: you can't work on the main document while the annotation
box is open on the screen. Too bad.

 It would be useful sometimes to be able to refer to the annotation while
making changes to the document - when making requested revisions to the
document, for example.

 Mac Word already had a voice annotation function that works much the
same as text annotation. It's odd that voice should have come first. Text
annotation is so much simpler and seemingly obvious an idea.

 If you use Word for preparing newsletters and you've often wondered how
to create a drop cap effect, with the first letter in a story enlarged
and the rest of the text running around it, wonder no more. With 5.1, you
can do it with a few keystrokes. You can 'drop cap' the first letter
only, the first word or a selected portion of text. And you can put the
drop cap in the margin or embed it in the text.

 Again, it seems so simple, you wonder why Microsoft didn't do it long
ago. It would be a nice feature to have in Word for Windows too. Are you
listening Bill?
