Title:     Word processing.
             (question-and-answer) (Here's How)(resolving problems in the
             use of WordPerfect 5.1, Word for Windows 2.0 and Ami
             Professional 2.0 word processing software packages)
Author:    Campbell, George
           Curtis, Jane
           Hurtado, Leo
           Clemont, Michel


-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Full Text:

Q I use WordPerfect 5.1 and like to store my documents in a directory
other than the one used by the program files. When I want to retrieve a
file, I use the <F5> (List Documents) command, but I'm tired of having to
type the new directory name to see my documents. How can I avoid this?

A WordPerfect is way ahead of you. To change the default directory for
your current session, press <F5>. When asked for a directory, press =,
type the directory path, and press <Enter>. The equal sign tells
WordPerfect to make the new directory the current default.

Of course, that default is changed when you exit WordPerfect. To
permanently change the default directory, press <Shift>-<F1>LD, type the
directory information, then press <Enter> three times. This won't affect
your current session, but the next time you load WordPerfect, that
directory will be your default, and pressing <F5><Enter> will bring you
to a list of its files.

Q I have a problem with sorting in WordPerfect 5.1. My document is a list
of titles, one per line. While WordPerfect sorts the first word of each
line correctly, the rest of the line isn't sorted. For example, In a
Mist, In Odessa, and In the Gloaming end up out of order. How can I get
an accurate sort?

A I can help sort out your problem. Since your document is a simple list
of titles, you can use WordPerfect's search-and- replace feature to
replace the spaces between words with "hard spaces," which WordPerfect
will ignore when sorting-in effect, seeing each title as a single word.

With your document loaded, press <Home><Home><Cursor Up> to make sure
you're at the top. To replace ordinary spaces with hard spaces, press
<Alt>-<F2>N<Space><F2><Home><Space><F2>. Press <Home><Home><Cursor Up>
again to return to the top of the document. If you press <Alt>-<F3>,
you'll see a hard space symbol ([ ]) between words.

Now for the sort: With the cursor still at the top of the page, press
<Ctrl>-<F9>S<Enter><Enter>P. Your list will be sorted perfectly. There's
no need to go back to the regular space characters if you won't be
justifying the titles.

Q I'm a screenwriter and need a word processing program that can produce
the exacting formatting required for screenplays and scripts. Is there
anything that will do this tough job?

A You're right, multiple columns and precise pagination requirements make
formatting a screenplay difficult. There is, however, an add-on program
for WordPerfect 5.1 designed just for the job. SuperScript Pro from ITE
Technologies works with WordPerfect by presetting the correct layouts for
feature films, TV situation comedies, TV dramas, and stage plays. You use
<Ctrl>-key combinations to handle formatting and other chores. Other
features let you insert scenes, change character names globally, and
more, allowing you to concentrate on the art of screenwriting rather than
the mechanics. The program sells for $159. Contact ITE Technologies,
310/559-3814.

Q I often need to edit other workers' Word for Windows 2.0 documents.
When I open one, I get the other person's WinWord font and formatting
preferences, but I'd rather see my own. I can redefine the styles, but
that's time-consuming. Is there a shortcut?

A This can be an annoying problem, particularly if the original author
used some bizarre font for the text. However, the solution is simple.
Instead of selecting File*Open to retrieve a document, start with a blank
document, then select Insert*File. Choose a document file, then select
OK. Any text that uses an unaltered style will use the style having the
same name in your default template. You'll get not only your preferred
fonts, but also your margin settings and other style-based formatting
attributes.

This won't work if your co-worker, in preparing the document, selected
text and chose a specific font or applied some other attribute. In that
case, you'll see that text in the fonts and attributes used by the
original author.

Q I'm writing a macro in Word for Windows 2.0 but have come up against a
stone wall. The macro must display the program's table creation dialog
box, let the user enter the desired number of rows and columns, then
insert the table in the document. I've tried everything I can think of,
but nothing seems to work. Everything else in my macro works fine. Do you
have a solution?

A The answer to this one is not obvious, and the Using WordBasic manual
and WinWord's macro help screens aren't clear. In your macro, wherever
you want to call the Insert Table dialog box, insert these four lines:

Dim MyDialog1 as TableInsertTable

GetCurValues MyDialog1

Dialog MyDialog1

TableInsertTable MyDialog1

Here's how it works: The first line defines the standard TableInsertTable
dialog box as the one you want to show. The next line tells WordBasic to
get the values when the user enters them. The third line actually
displays the dialog box, while the fourth line uses the values the user
enters to actually create the table. You can use the same structure to
display any WinWord dialog box for user input, using any name you like to
replace 'MyDialog1'.

Q I use Word for Windows 2.0 often and would like to be able to preview
and delete files in the program without switching to File Manager. Can
WinWord handle this chore for me?

A In November 1992's Dialog Box column, we offered a simple macro for
quickly deleting files from within Word for Windows. For loading,
previewing, copying, and deleting files, however, you'd do best using
WinWord 2.0's capable file management system, which many users don't know
about. Here's how to proceed:

Select File*Find File. If the file you want is in your current directory
and is a WinWord document, you'll see it in the list box. Click on a file
name to bring up a preview of the document in miniature, and select
Delete to delete the file. You won't be able to delete any files
currently loaded into WinWord, however. To select more than one file for
deletion, hold down the <Ctrl> key while you click on the file names.

If the file or files you want to preview or delete aren't in your current
directory, you'll have to go a bit further. As before, select File*Find
File, then select Search. In the next dialog box, Search, click the Edit
Path button. In the Edit Path dialog box, navigate the tree in the
Directories box-changing drives in the Drive box if necessary-to
highlight the directory you want to search, then click Add. You can add
more directories to the Search Path box if you want. Click Close or press
<Esc>. Back in the Search dialog box, select Start Search. When WinWord
finishes the search, you'll return to the previous dialog box, where you
can delete any files in the list.

Q I like the table feature in Ami Professional 2.0, but the tables must
be centered or aligned with the left margin. I need to position a table
in another location. Can Ami Pro do this?

A No problem. The trick here-and it's not obvious until you try it-is to
put your table in a frame, rather than on the base page itself. Start by
selecting Frame* Create Frame*Manual. With the mouse, move the frame
cursor to the upper left corner of the position for your table, then hold
down the left button while you drag the frame to the size you want. Next,
release the mouse button, and select Tools*Tables, set the number of
columns and rows you want, and select OK.

Now, with the empty table inside the frame, you can use Ami Pro's Table
commands to fill in the table. If you want to edit the table later, all
you have to do is double-click inside the frame. As with all Ami Pro
frames, you can position or resize your table frame at any time.

